u>And your life</u></i>\r\n<i><u>doesn't flash before</u> you...</i>\r\n\r\n1289\r\n01:30:23,800 --> 01:30:26,189\r\n<i>...because <u>you're too scared</u></i>\r\n<i><u>to think.</u></i>\r\n\r\n1290\r\n01:30:26,480 --> 01:30:29,392\r\n<i><u>You</u> just freeze</i>\r\n<i><u>and pull</u> a <u>stupid</u> face.</i>\r\n\r\n1291\r\n01:30:29,680 --> 01:30:31,796\r\n<i><u>But the pikey didn't. Why?</u></i>\r\n\r\n1292\r\n01:30:32,040 --> 01:30:34,713\r\n<i>Because <u>he had plans</u></i>\r\n<i><u>on running the car over.</u></i>\r\n\r\n1293\r\n01:30:37,040 --> 01:30:39,031\r\n<i>It <u>had previously occurred to</u> me...</i>\r\n\r\n1294\r\n01:30:39,320 --> 01:30:42,437\r\n<i>... that <u>he'd taken the</u> demise</i>\r\n<i><u>of his mother rather lightly.</u></i>\r\n\r\n1295\r\n01:30:45,520 --> 01:30:48,114\r\n<i><u>For every action,</u></i>\r\n<i><u>there is</u> a <u>reaction.</i></u>\r\n\r\n1296\r\n01:30:48,400 --> 01:30:50,197\r\n<i><u>And</u> a <u>pikey</u> reaction...</i>\r\n\r\n1297\r\n01:30:50,880 --> 01:30:52,154\r\n<i>... <u>is</u> quite a <u>fucking thing.</u></i>\r\n\r\n1298\r\n01:31:32,480 --> 01:31:34,436\r\nPete, talk to me.\r\n\r\n1299\r\n01:31:34,680 --> 01:31:38,116\r\nIf you want your friend to hear you,\r\ntalk a lot louder than that.\r\n\r\n1300\r\n01:31:46,760 --> 01:31:50,150\r\n- Give me that fucking shooter.\r\n- I'll give you your shooter, you cunt.\r\n\r\n1301\r\n01:31:57,880 --> 01:32:01,350\r\n<i>That <u>is when</u> I <u>thought the pikey</u></i>\r\n<i><u>had money riding on</u> himself.</i>\r\n\r\n1302\r\n01:32:02,360 --> 01:32:05,716\r\n<i>That's <u>why the</u> bastard <u>never</u></i>\r\n<i>goes <u>down when</u> he's <u>supposed to.</u></i>\r\n\r\n1303\r\n01:32:07,440 --> 01:32:09,112\r\n<i><u>We've been tucked</u> up...</i>\r\n\r\n1304\r\n01:32:10,720 --> 01:32:12,233\r\n<i>... <u>while</u> he's <u>been cleaning up.</u></i>\r\n\r\n1305\r\n01:32:14,320 --> 01:32:16,788\r\n<i><u>We're worse</u> off <u>now than</u></i>\r\n<i><u>when</u> we started.</i>\r\n\r\n1306\r\n01:32:22,080 --> 01:32:24,389\r\n<i><u>The</u> next <u>day</u> we <u>went</u></i>\r\n<i><u>to the</u> campsite...</i>\r\n\r\n1307\r\n01:32:24,680 --> 01:32:27,672\r\n<i>...but <u>the gypsies had disappeared</u></i>\r\n<i><u>during the night.</u></i>\r\n\r\n1308\r\n01:32:27,920 --> 01:32:29,797\r\n<i><u>Which</u> was <u>probably</u> a <u>good</u> thing...</i>\r\n\r\n1309\r\n01:32:30,080 --> 01:32:34,278\r\n<i>... <u>considering they'd</u> just <u>buried</u></i>\r\n<i>12 <u>people</u> somewhere <u>in the</u> area.</i>\r\n\r\n1310\r\n01:32:34,600 --> 01:32:35,874\r\nWhere is he?\r\n\r\n1311\r\n01:32:36,160 --> 01:32:38,151\r\nHe ain't fucking here,\r\nthat's for sure.\r\n\r\n1312\r\n01:32:38,960 --> 01:32:42,316\r\nWe can't ask a man to fight for us\r\nif we can't find him, can we?\r\n\r\n1313\r\n01:32:42,560 --> 01:32:45,677\r\nYou won't find a pikey that\r\ndoesn't want to be found.\r\n\r\n1314\r\n01:32:47,800 --> 01:32:50,872\r\nHe could be in a campsite\r\nin Kampu-fucking-chea by now.\r\n\r\n1315\r\n01:32:52,400 --> 01:32:54,118\r\nBollocks! Come on.\r\n\r\n1316\r\n01:32:59,200 --> 01:33:01,873\r\n- What you doing here?\r\n- What's it got to do with you?\r\n\r\n1317\r\n01:33:05,640 --> 01:33:07,676\r\nSo, what you doing here?\r\n\r\n1318\r\n01:33:15,000 --> 01:33:17,719\r\nI'm taking the dog for a walk.\r\nWhat's the problem?\r\n\r\n1319\r\n01:33:19,360 --> 01:33:20,190\r\nWhat's in the car?\r\n\r\n1320\r\n01:33:20,880 --> 01:33:22,313\r\nSeats and a steering wheel.\r\n\r\n1321\r\n01:33:23,440 --> 01:33:25,158\r\nWhat do you know about gypsies?\r\n\r\n1322\r\n01:33:26,880 --> 01:33:28,757\r\nI know they're not to be trusted.\r\n\r\n1323\r\n01:33:30,760 --> 01:33:33,320\r\nAll right, get your dog. On your way.\r\n\r\n1324\r\n01:33:34,160 --> 01:33:35,593\r\nGet the dog, Tommy.\r\n\r\n1325\r\n01:33:37,400 --> 01:33:38,594\r\nThe dog.\r\n\r\n1326\r\n01:33:40,120 --> 01:33:44,398\r\nAll right, boy. Come on.\r\nCome on, Daisy. No, Daisy!\r\n\r\n1327\r\n01:33:45,120 --> 01:33:46,712\r\nHe loves that dog.\r\n\r\n1328\r\n01:33:47,080 --> 01:33:48,718\r\nAlways playing silly games.\r\n\r\n1329\r\n01:33:48,960 --> 01:33:52,191\r\nStop messing about\r\nand get it in the car. Tommy!\r\n\r\n1330\r\n01:33:54,000 --> 01:33:58,551\r\nGood boy. Good boy.\r\nGood boy, Daisy, good boy.\r\n\r\n1331\r\n01:34:08,920 --> 01:34:10,353\r\nCould you tell me...\r\n\r\n1332\r\n01:34:10,640 --> 01:34:13,712\r\n...why you got a dead man\r\nwith an arm missing in your boot?\r\n\r\n1333\r\n01:34:14,320 --> 01:34:15,275\r\nHey, George...\r\n\r\n1334\r\n01:34:16,640 --> 01:34:18,710\r\n...is that a tea cosy on his head?\r\n\r\n1335\r\n01:34:22,000 --> 01:34:24,309\r\nOh, you love a dog, don't you, Tommy?\r\n\r\n1336\r\n01:34:33,840 --> 01:34:36,274\r\n<i><u>Tommy</u> persuaded me <u>to keep the dog.</u></i>\r\n\r\n1337\r\n01:34:36,520 --> 01:34:39,990\r\n<i>I <u>eventually</u> agreed,</i>\r\n<i>as <u>long</u> as <u>he took it to</u> a vet.</i>\r\n\r\n1338\r\n01:34:40,240 --> 01:34:42,595\r\n<i>I <u>couldn't stand</u></i>\r\n<i>that squeaking <u>anymore.</u></i>\r\n\r\n1339\r\n01:34:42,880 --> 01:34:46,077\r\n<i><u>The</u> vet <u>found half an</u> undigested</i>\r\n<i><u>shoe,</u> a squeaky toy...</i>\r\n\r\n1340\r\n01:34:46,320 --> 01:34:49,471\r\n<i>... <u>and an</u> 84-carat <u>diamond</u></i>\r\n<i><u>lodged in</u> its <u>stomach.</u></i>\r\n\r\n1341\r\n01:34:50,080 --> 01:34:52,469\r\n<i>It's quite <u>amazing</u> what <u>can happen</u></i>\r\n<i><u>in</u> a week.</i>\r\n\r\n1342\r\n01:34:52,880 --> 01:34:54,757\r\n<i><u>Still didn't</u> shut <u>it up, though.</u></i>\r\n\r\n1343\r\n01:34:55,640 --> 01:34:57,392\r\n<i><u>So,</u> what <u>do you do?</u></i>\r\n\r\n1344\r\n01:34:57,680 --> 01:35:00,433\r\n<i><u>You go</u> see <u>the man</u> that <u>knows</u></i>\r\n<i><u>about</u> these <u>sort of things.</u></i>\r\n\r\n1345\r\n01:35:00,680 --> 01:35:02,159\r\nSo, what do you think?\r\n\r\n1346\r\n01:35:03,880 --> 01:35:05,950\r\nDo you know anyone\r\nwho'd be interested?\r\n\r\n1347\r\n01:35:10,680 --> 01:35:11,476\r\nI might.\r\n\r\n1348\r\n01:38:26,520 --> 01:38:27,475\r\nSubtitles by\r\nGelulalSDI\r\n\r\n","markerStore":{"nextMarkerId":132,"markersById":{"0":{"range":{"start":{"row":1861,"column":12},"end":{"row":1861,"column":12}},"properties":{"type":"selection","editorId":112,"goalScreenRange":null},"reversed":false,"tailed":false,"valid":true,"invalidate":"never","maintainHistory":true}},"version":2},"history":{"version":3,"nextCheckpointId":1,"undoStack":[],"redoStack":[]},"encoding":"utf8","filePath":"/Users/joegesualdo/Downloads/snatch.(2000).eng.1cd.(5994372)/Snatch. (2000).CD1.srt","digestWhenLastPersisted":"d6b123d92b145b34a467f626fbfe3fde4edfac0e","preferredLineEnding":null,"deserializer":"TextBuffer","version":2},{"load":true,"text":"1\r\n00:00:00,599 --> 00:00:04,196\r\nSubtitles downloaded from www.OpenSubtitles.org\r\n\r\n2\r\n00:02:25,438 --> 00:02:26,661\r\nAll right, Charlie.\r\n\r\n3\r\n00:02:26,685 --> 00:02:29,131\r\n- That the joint? Who runs it?\n- I already told you.\r\n\r\n4\r\n00:02:29,155 --> 00:02:30,449\r\n- Refresh my memory.\n- Spats Colombo.\r\n\r\n5\r\n00:02:30,473 --> 00:02:32,415\r\n- What's the password?\n- \"I've come to Grandma's funeral.\"\r\n\r\n6\r\n00:02:32,439 --> 00:02:33,734\r\n- Your admission card.\n- Thanks, Charlie.\r\n\r\n7\r\n00:02:33,758 --> 00:02:35,844\r\nIf you want a ringside table,\njust say you're a pallbearer.\r\n\r\n8\r\n00:02:35,868 --> 00:02:37,091\r\nWe're all set. Whens the kickoff?\r\n\r\n9\r\n00:02:37,115 --> 00:02:38,961\r\nI'd better blow.\nIf Colombo sees me, it's goodbye, Charlie.\r\n\r\n10\r\n00:02:38,985 --> 00:02:40,999\r\nGoodbye, Charlie.\r\n\r\n11\r\n00:02:41,023 --> 00:02:42,797\r\nGive me five minutes,\nthen hit 'em with everything you got.\r\n\r\n12\r\n00:02:42,821 --> 00:02:44,595\r\nYou betcha.\r\n\r\n13\r\n00:02:52,675 --> 00:02:53,610\r\nGood evening, sir.\r\n\r\n14\r\n00:02:53,634 --> 00:02:55,768\r\n- I'm Mr Mozarella. What can I do for you?\n- I've come to the old lady's funeral.\r\n\r\n15\r\n00:02:55,792 --> 00:02:57,207\r\nI haven't seen you at our services before.\r\n\r\n16\r\n00:02:57,231 --> 00:02:58,573\r\n- No, I've been on the wagon.\n- Please.\r\n\r\n17\r\n00:02:58,597 --> 00:03:00,132\r\nWhere is the wake?\nI'm one of the pallbearers.\r\n\r\n18\r\n00:03:00,156 --> 00:03:01,930\r\nShow the gentleman into the chapel.\nPew number three.\r\n\r\n19\r\n00:03:01,954 --> 00:03:04,999\r\nYes, Mr Mozarella. This way, sir.\r\n\r\n20\r\n00:03:13,774 --> 00:03:15,356\r\nWell, if you gotta go,\nthat's the way to do it.\r\n\r\n21\r\n00:03:15,380 --> 00:03:17,562\r\nFollow me, please.\r\n\r\n22\r\n00:03:23,772 --> 00:03:24,947\r\n- What'll it be, sir?\n- Booze.\r\n\r\n23\r\n00:03:24,971 --> 00:03:26,337\r\n- Sorry. We only serve coffee.\n- Coffee?\r\n\r\n24\r\n00:03:26,361 --> 00:03:28,064\r\nScotch coffee, Canadian coffee,\nsour mash coffee...\r\n\r\n25\r\n00:03:28,088 --> 00:03:29,742\r\nScotch. Make it a demitasse,\nwith soda on the side.\r\n\r\n26\r\n00:03:29,766 --> 00:03:31,972\r\nWait a minute. Haven't you got\na pew not so close to the band?\r\n\r\n27\r\n00:03:31,996 --> 00:03:33,171\r\nHow about that one over there?\r\n\r\n28\r\n00:03:33,195 --> 00:03:37,966\r\nSorry, but that's reserved\nfor members of the immediate family.\r\n\r\n29\r\n00:03:41,035 --> 00:03:42,473\r\nOops.\r\n\r\n30\r\n00:03:45,470 --> 00:03:47,245\r\nHey, I want another cup of coffee.\r\n\r\n31\r\n00:03:47,269 --> 00:03:50,074\r\nI want another cup of coffee.\r\n\r\n32\r\n00:03:55,061 --> 00:03:56,547\r\nBetter bring a check\nin case the joint is raided.\r\n\r\n33\r\n00:03:56,571 --> 00:04:01,582\r\n- Who's gonna raid a funeral?\n- Some people don't respect the dead.\r\n\r\n34\r\n00:04:12,563 --> 00:04:14,098\r\nSay, Joe. Tonight's the night, isn't it?\r\n\r\n35\r\n00:04:14,122 --> 00:04:16,136\r\n- I'll say.\n- No, tonight we get paid.\r\n\r\n36\r\n00:04:16,160 --> 00:04:18,293\r\n- Why?\n- I've got to see a dentist tomorrow.\r\n\r\n37\r\n00:04:18,317 --> 00:04:20,092\r\nYou wanna blow\nyour first week's pay on your teeth?\r\n\r\n38\r\n00:04:20,116 --> 00:04:22,369\r\nJust a filling. Doesn't have to be gold.\r\n\r\n39\r\n00:04:22,393 --> 00:04:25,007\r\nHow can you be so selfish? We owe rent.\nWe owe $89 to Moe's Delicatessen.\r\n\r\n40\r\n00:04:25,031 --> 00:04:27,524\r\nThe Chinese laundry is suing us.\nWe owe money to every girl in the line.\r\n\r\n41\r\n00:04:27,548 --> 00:04:29,922\r\nYou're right. Tomorrow we'll pay\neveryone something on account.\r\n\r\n42\r\n00:04:29,946 --> 00:04:32,991\r\nNo. Tomorrow we go to the dog track\nand bet it all on Greased Lightning.\r\n\r\n43\r\n00:04:33,015 --> 00:04:34,669\r\n- You'd bet my money on a dog?\n- He's a shoo-in.\r\n\r\n44\r\n00:04:34,693 --> 00:04:36,515\r\nMax the waiter knows the electrician\nthat wires the rabbit.\r\n\r\n45\r\n00:04:36,539 --> 00:04:38,793\r\n- What are you givin' me with a rabbit?\n- The odds are 10 to 1.\r\n\r\n46\r\n00:04:38,817 --> 00:04:40,975\r\n- Suppose he loses.\n- Why worry? This job'll last a long time.\r\n\r\n47\r\n00:04:40,999 --> 00:04:43,372\r\n- Suppose it doesn't.\n- Jerry boy, why paint everyzhing black?\r\n\r\n48\r\n00:04:43,396 --> 00:04:46,082\r\nSuppose you got hit by a truck.\nSuppose the stock market crashes.\r\n\r\n49\r\n00:04:46,106 --> 00:04:47,808\r\nSuppose Mary Pickford\ndivorces Douglas Fairbanks.\r\n\r\n50\r\n00:04:47,832 --> 00:04:49,606\r\nSuppose the Dodgers leave Brooklyn.\r\n\r\n51\r\n00:04:49,630 --> 00:04:50,805\r\nSuppose Lake Michigan overflows.\r\n\r\n52\r\n00:04:50,829 --> 00:04:55,145\r\nWell, don't look now,\nbut the whole town is underwater.\r\n\r\n53\r\n00:05:00,419 --> 00:05:01,115\r\nFour,\r\n\r\n54\r\n00:05:01,139 --> 00:05:02,026\r\nthree,\r\n\r\n55\r\n00:05:02,050 --> 00:05:02,913\r\ntwo,\r\n\r\n56\r\n00:05:02,937 --> 00:05:04,327\r\none.\r\n\r\n57\r\n00:05:11,041 --> 00:05:13,103\r\nAll right, everybody. This is a raid.\r\n\r\n58\r\n00:05:13,127 --> 00:05:15,141\r\nI'm a federal agent.\nYou're all under arrest.\r\n\r\n59\r\n00:05:15,165 --> 00:05:17,970\r\nI want another cup of coffee.\r\n\r\n60\r\n00:05:23,676 --> 00:05:24,731\r\nAll right, Spats.\r\n\r\n61\r\n00:05:24,755 --> 00:05:26,409\r\n- The services are over. Let's go.\n- Go where?\r\n\r\n62\r\n00:05:26,433 --> 00:05:28,807\r\nA country club for retired bootleggers.\nI'm puttin' you up for membership.\r\n\r\n63\r\n00:05:28,831 --> 00:05:30,605\r\n- I don't join nothin'.\n- Oh, you'll like it there.\r\n\r\n64\r\n00:05:30,629 --> 00:05:33,314\r\nI'll get the prison tailor to fit you\nwith a pair of special spats - striped.\r\n\r\n65\r\n00:05:33,338 --> 00:05:35,161\r\nBig joke. What's the rap this time?\r\n\r\n66\r\n00:05:35,184 --> 00:05:37,678\r\nEmbalming people with coffee. 86 proof.\r\n\r\n67\r\n00:05:37,702 --> 00:05:38,877\r\nMe? I'm just a customer.\r\n\r\n68\r\n00:05:38,901 --> 00:05:42,114\r\nOh, come on, Spats. We know you own\nthe joint. Mozarella's just frontin' for you.\r\n\r\n69\r\n00:05:42,138 --> 00:05:44,703\r\n- Mozarella? Never heard of him.\n- We got different information.\r\n\r\n70\r\n00:05:44,727 --> 00:05:46,429\r\nFrom who? Toothpick Charlie maybe?\r\n\r\n71\r\n00:05:46,453 --> 00:05:49,258\r\nToothpick Charlie? Never heard of him.\r\n\r\n72\r\n00:05:49,282 --> 00:05:50,937\r\nButtermilk.\r\n\r\n73\r\n00:05:50,961 --> 00:05:52,543\r\nToo smart to drink your own stuff, huh?\r\n\r\n74\r\n00:05:52,567 --> 00:05:54,341\r\nCome on. On your feet.\r\n\r\n75\r\n00:05:54,365 --> 00:05:56,619\r\n- You're wastin' the taxpayers' money.\n- Call your lawyer if you wanna.\r\n\r\n76\r\n00:05:56,643 --> 00:05:59,976\r\nThese are my lawyers. All Harvard men.\r\n\r\n77\r\n00:06:03,188 --> 00:06:05,946\r\nI wan' another cuppa coffee.\r\n\r\n78\r\n00:06:26,805 --> 00:06:28,939\r\nThat solves one problem. Now we don't\nhave to worry about who to pay first.\r\n\r\n79\r\n00:06:28,963 --> 00:06:30,665\r\n- Quiet. I'm thinking.\n- The landlady will lock us out.\r\n\r\n80\r\n00:06:30,689 --> 00:06:32,247\r\nAt Moe's Deli no\nmore knockwurst on credit.\r\n\r\n81\r\n00:06:32,271 --> 00:06:34,285\r\nWe can't borrow from the girls -\nthey're on the way to jail.\r\n\r\n82\r\n00:06:34,309 --> 00:06:36,275\r\nI wonder how much Sam the bookie\nwill give us for our overcoats.\r\n\r\n83\r\n00:06:36,299 --> 00:06:39,033\r\nSam the bookie? Nothin' doin'.\nYou're not puttin' my overcoat on a dog.\r\n\r\n84\r\n00:06:39,057 --> 00:06:40,879\r\n- Jerry, I told you, it's a sure thing.\n- We will freeze.\r\n\r\n85\r\n00:06:40,903 --> 00:06:42,389\r\nIt is below zero. We'll get pneumonia.\r\n\r\n86\r\n00:06:42,413 --> 00:06:46,897\r\nLook, stupid, he's 10-1.\nTomorrow we'll have 20 overcoats.\r\n\r\n87\r\n00:06:50,445 --> 00:06:51,500\r\nGreased Lightning.\r\n\r\n88\r\n00:06:51,524 --> 00:06:53,826\r\n- I oughta have my head examined.\n- I thought you weren't talkin' to me.\r\n\r\n89\r\n00:06:53,850 --> 00:06:57,470\r\nThe bull fiddle's\ndressed warmer than I am.\r\n\r\n90\r\n00:06:59,604 --> 00:07:00,659\r\n- Anyzhing today?\n- Nothing.\r\n\r\n91\r\n00:07:00,683 --> 00:07:02,409\r\nThank you.\r\n\r\n92\r\n00:07:03,080 --> 00:07:04,207\r\n- Anyzhing today?\n- Nothing.\r\n\r\n93\r\n00:07:04,231 --> 00:07:05,214\r\nThank you.\r\n\r\n94\r\n00:07:05,238 --> 00:07:07,804\r\nI can't go on, Joe. I'm weak from hunger,\nI got a fever, I got a hole in my shoe...\r\n\r\n95\r\n00:07:07,828 --> 00:07:09,482\r\nIf you gave me a chance,\nwe could be living like kings.\r\n\r\n96\r\n00:07:09,506 --> 00:07:10,801\r\n- How?\n- There's a dog running in the third.\r\n\r\n97\r\n00:07:10,825 --> 00:07:13,438\r\nGalloping Ghost. He's 15-1 and it's\nhis kind of a track. He's a real mudder.\r\n\r\n98\r\n00:07:13,462 --> 00:07:15,045\r\nWhat do you want from me?\nMy head on a plate?\r\n\r\n99\r\n00:07:15,068 --> 00:07:16,723\r\nNo, your bass.\nIf we hock that and my sax...\r\n\r\n100\r\n00:07:16,747 --> 00:07:18,881\r\nAre you crazy? We're up the creek\nand you wanna hock the paddle.\r\n\r\n101\r\n00:07:18,905 --> 00:07:20,751\r\nAll right, go ahead and starve.\nWhat do I care? Freeze.\r\n\r\n102\r\n00:07:20,775 --> 00:07:22,357\r\n- Anyzhing today?\n- Oh, it's you.\r\n\r\n103\r\n00:07:22,381 --> 00:07:23,628\r\nWell, you've got a lot of nerve.\r\n\r\n104\r\n00:07:23,652 --> 00:07:24,827\r\nThank you.\r\n\r\n105\r\n00:07:24,851 --> 00:07:27,152\r\nJoe. Come back here.\r\n\r\n106\r\n00:07:28,375 --> 00:07:30,461\r\nNellie, baby, if it's about Saturday night,\nI can explain.\r\n\r\n107\r\n00:07:30,485 --> 00:07:32,379\r\nWhat a heel. I spend $4\nto get my hair marcelled,\r\n\r\n108\r\n00:07:32,403 --> 00:07:33,626\r\nI buy me a brand-new negligee,\r\n\r\n109\r\n00:07:33,650 --> 00:07:34,945\r\nI bake him a great big pizza pie.\r\n\r\n110\r\n00:07:34,969 --> 00:07:36,743\r\n- And where were you?\n- Where were you?\r\n\r\n111\r\n00:07:36,767 --> 00:07:37,534\r\n- With you.\n- Me?\r\n\r\n112\r\n00:07:37,558 --> 00:07:38,733\r\nRemember? You had this bad tooth.\r\n\r\n113\r\n00:07:38,757 --> 00:07:40,051\r\nIt was impacted. His jaw was swoll out.\r\n\r\n114\r\n00:07:40,075 --> 00:07:40,771\r\nIt was?\r\n\r\n115\r\n00:07:40,795 --> 00:07:42,018\r\nOh, yeah.\r\n\r\n116\r\n00:07:42,041 --> 00:07:44,055\r\n- I took him for a blood transfusion.\n- We have the same type blood.\r\n\r\n117\r\n00:07:44,079 --> 00:07:45,734\r\n- Type O.\n- Oh?\r\n\r\n118\r\n00:07:45,758 --> 00:07:48,131\r\n- I'll make it up to you.\n- You're makin' it up pretty good so far.\r\n\r\n119\r\n00:07:48,155 --> 00:07:50,769\r\nAs soon as we get a job, I'll take you\nto the swellest restaurant in town.\r\n\r\n120\r\n00:07:50,793 --> 00:07:53,046\r\nHow about it? Has Poliakoff got\nanyzhing for us? We're desperate.\r\n\r\n121\r\n00:07:53,070 --> 00:07:55,276\r\nWell, it just so happens\nhe is looking for a bass.\r\n\r\n122\r\n00:07:55,300 --> 00:07:56,283\r\nAnd a sax.\r\n\r\n123\r\n00:07:56,307 --> 00:07:57,242\r\nRight?\r\n\r\n124\r\n00:07:57,266 --> 00:07:58,153\r\nRight.\r\n\r\n125\r\n00:07:58,177 --> 00:07:59,880\r\n- What's the job?\n- Three weeks in Florida.\r\n\r\n126\r\n00:07:59,904 --> 00:08:02,229\r\nAt the Seminole-Ritz in Miami.\nTransportation and expenses all paid.\r\n\r\n127\r\n00:08:02,253 --> 00:08:04,075\r\nIsn't she a bit of terrific?\nLet's see Poliakoff.\r\n\r\n128\r\n00:08:04,099 --> 00:08:06,233\r\n- He's busy. You'll have to wait, boys.\n- All right, we'll wait.\r\n\r\n129\r\n00:08:06,257 --> 00:08:07,792\r\nLook, Gladys, it's three weeks in Florida.\r\n\r\n130\r\n00:08:07,816 --> 00:08:09,230\r\nSweet Sue and her Society Syncopators.\r\n\r\n131\r\n00:08:09,254 --> 00:08:11,148\r\nThey need a couple of girls\non sax and bass.\r\n\r\n132\r\n00:08:11,172 --> 00:08:13,378\r\nWhaddaya mean, who is it?\nIt's Poliakoff. I got a job for ya.\r\n\r\n133\r\n00:08:13,402 --> 00:08:14,457\r\nGladys. Are ya there?\r\n\r\n134\r\n00:08:14,481 --> 00:08:15,824\r\nGladys!\r\n\r\n135\r\n00:08:15,848 --> 00:08:17,694\r\nMeshugeneh.\nPlayed 112 hours at a marathon dance.\r\n\r\n136\r\n00:08:17,718 --> 00:08:19,660\r\n- Now she's in bed with nervous collapse.\n- Tell her to move over.\r\n\r\n137\r\n00:08:19,684 --> 00:08:20,619\r\nAnd Cora Jackson?\r\n\r\n138\r\n00:08:20,643 --> 00:08:22,729\r\nLast I heard, she was playin'\nwith the Salvation Army.\r\n\r\n139\r\n00:08:22,753 --> 00:08:23,976\r\nDrexel 9044.\r\n\r\n140\r\n00:08:23,999 --> 00:08:25,246\r\nThose idiot broads.\r\n\r\n141\r\n00:08:25,270 --> 00:08:27,476\r\nHere we are, packed and ready to leave\nfor Miami, and what happens?\r\n\r\n142\r\n00:08:27,500 --> 00:08:30,593\r\nThe sax runs off with a Bible salesman\nand the bass gets pregnant.\r\n\r\n143\r\n00:08:30,617 --> 00:08:31,792\r\nBienstock, I oughta fire you.\r\n\r\n144\r\n00:08:31,816 --> 00:08:33,782\r\nMe? I'm the manager,\nnot the night watchman.\r\n\r\n145\r\n00:08:33,806 --> 00:08:35,388\r\nHello. Let me talk to Bessie Malone.\r\n\r\n146\r\n00:08:35,412 --> 00:08:36,899\r\nWhat's she doing in Philadelphia?\r\n\r\n147\r\n00:08:36,923 --> 00:08:38,385\r\nOn the level?\r\n\r\n148\r\n00:08:38,409 --> 00:08:40,015\r\nBessie let her hair grow\nand is playing with Stokowski.\r\n\r\n149\r\n00:08:40,039 --> 00:08:42,533\r\n- Black Bottom Bessie?\n- Schpielt zich mit der Philharmonic.\r\n\r\n150\r\n00:08:42,557 --> 00:08:43,420\r\nHow about Rosemary Schultz?\r\n\r\n151\r\n00:08:43,444 --> 00:08:44,739\r\nSlashed her wrists when Valentino died.\r\n\r\n152\r\n00:08:44,763 --> 00:08:46,969\r\nWe might as well do the same\nif we don't find two dames by tonight.\r\n\r\n153\r\n00:08:46,992 --> 00:08:49,606\r\nWe don't care where you find them.\nJust get them on that train by 8 o'clock.\r\n\r\n154\r\n00:08:49,630 --> 00:08:51,932\r\nThe moment anyzhing turns up,\nI'll give you a tinkle.\r\n\r\n155\r\n00:08:51,956 --> 00:08:53,610\r\nBye, Sig. I wonder\nif I've got room for another ulcer.\r\n\r\n156\r\n00:08:53,634 --> 00:08:55,000\r\nNellie, get me long-distance.\r\n\r\n157\r\n00:08:55,024 --> 00:08:57,566\r\n- Sig, we wanna talk to you.\n- About the Florida job.\r\n\r\n158\r\n00:08:57,590 --> 00:08:59,076\r\n- Nellie told us about it.\n- Not too late, are we?\r\n\r\n159\r\n00:08:59,100 --> 00:09:00,515\r\nWhat are ya? Comedians? Get out.\r\n\r\n160\r\n00:09:00,539 --> 00:09:02,193\r\nThe William Morris Agency in New York.\r\n\r\n161\r\n00:09:02,217 --> 00:09:04,399\r\n- You need a bass and a sax?\n- The instruments are right but you're not.\r\n\r\n162\r\n00:09:04,423 --> 00:09:05,310\r\nI wanna speak to Mr Morris.\r\n\r\n163\r\n00:09:05,334 --> 00:09:06,869\r\n- What's wrong with us?\n- You're the wrong shape.\r\n\r\n164\r\n00:09:06,893 --> 00:09:09,314\r\n- What do you want? Hunchbacks?\n- It's not the backs that worry me.\r\n\r\n165\r\n00:09:09,338 --> 00:09:10,225\r\nWhat kind of a band is it?\r\n\r\n166\r\n00:09:10,249 --> 00:09:11,592\r\n- You gotta be under 25.\n- We could pass for that.\r\n\r\n167\r\n00:09:11,616 --> 00:09:12,623\r\n- And blond.\n- We could dye our hair.\r\n\r\n168\r\n00:09:12,647 --> 00:09:13,462\r\nAnd you gotta be girls.\r\n\r\n169\r\n00:09:13,486 --> 00:09:14,181\r\nNo, we couldn't.\r\n\r\n170\r\n00:09:14,205 --> 00:09:16,027\r\n- Mr William Morris.\n- You mean this is a girls' band?\r\n\r\n171\r\n00:09:16,051 --> 00:09:18,185\r\nYeah. Good old Nellie.\nI could wring her neck.\r\n\r\n172\r\n00:09:18,209 --> 00:09:19,624\r\nLet's talk this over. Why couldn't we do it?\r\n\r\n173\r\n00:09:19,648 --> 00:09:21,542\r\nWhen we worked in the gypsy tearoom,\nwe wore gold earrings.\r\n\r\n174\r\n00:09:21,566 --> 00:09:23,532\r\nWhen you booked us with\nthe Hawaiian band, we wore grass skirts.\r\n\r\n175\r\n00:09:23,556 --> 00:09:25,378\r\n- What's with him? He drinks?\n- No, he ain't eatin' so good.\r\n\r\n176\r\n00:09:25,402 --> 00:09:26,697\r\nHis empty stomach has gone to his head.\r\n\r\n177\r\n00:09:26,721 --> 00:09:29,046\r\nJoe, three weeks in Florida. We could\nborrow clothes from the chorus girls.\r\n\r\n178\r\n00:09:29,070 --> 00:09:31,012\r\n- You've flipped your wig.\n- Now you're talking.\r\n\r\n179\r\n00:09:31,036 --> 00:09:32,571\r\nWe get second-hand wigs, a little padding.\r\n\r\n180\r\n00:09:32,595 --> 00:09:34,129\r\nWe call ourselves\nJosephine and Geraldine.\r\n\r\n181\r\n00:09:34,153 --> 00:09:36,119\r\nJosephine and Geraldine... Come on.\r\n\r\n182\r\n00:09:36,143 --> 00:09:37,606\r\nIf you wanna pick up\na little money tonight,\r\n\r\n183\r\n00:09:37,630 --> 00:09:40,003\r\nat the University of Illinois\nthey're havin' a St Valentine's dance.\r\n\r\n184\r\n00:09:40,027 --> 00:09:40,962\r\nWe'll take it.\r\n\r\n185\r\n00:09:40,986 --> 00:09:42,641\r\n$6 a man. Be on the campus\nat Urbana at 8 o'clock.\r\n\r\n186\r\n00:09:42,665 --> 00:09:44,271\r\nAll the way to Urbana\nfor a one-night stand?\r\n\r\n187\r\n00:09:44,295 --> 00:09:46,117\r\nIt's $12. We can get\none of the overcoats out of hock.\r\n\r\n188\r\n00:09:46,141 --> 00:09:48,275\r\nHello. Mr Morris?\nThis is Poliakoff in Chicago.\r\n\r\n189\r\n00:09:48,299 --> 00:09:49,953\r\nYou don't have two girl musicians\navailable, do you?\r\n\r\n190\r\n00:09:49,977 --> 00:09:50,984\r\nA sax player and a bass?\r\n\r\n191\r\n00:09:51,008 --> 00:09:54,341\r\n- If William Morris doesn't come through...\n- Come on, Geraldine.\r\n\r\n192\r\n00:09:54,365 --> 00:09:56,187\r\nIt's 100 miles. It's snowin' outside.\nHow do we get there?\r\n\r\n193\r\n00:09:56,211 --> 00:09:57,386\r\n- I'll find something.\n- Like what?\r\n\r\n194\r\n00:09:57,410 --> 00:09:58,825\r\nDon't crowd me.\r\n\r\n195\r\n00:09:58,849 --> 00:10:00,934\r\n- How'd it go, girls?\n- I oughta wring your neck.\r\n\r\n196\r\n00:10:00,958 --> 00:10:02,900\r\nPlease, Jerry. That's no way to talk.\r\n\r\n197\r\n00:10:02,924 --> 00:10:04,411\r\nNellie baby, what are you doin' tonight?\r\n\r\n198\r\n00:10:04,435 --> 00:10:06,617\r\n- Tonight? Why?\n- Cos I've got some plans.\r\n\r\n199\r\n00:10:06,641 --> 00:10:08,727\r\n- I'm not doing anything.\n- Really?\r\n\r\n200\r\n00:10:08,751 --> 00:10:11,172\r\nI just thought I'd go home\nand have some cold pizza.\r\n\r\n201\r\n00:10:11,196 --> 00:10:12,371\r\nThen you'll be in all evening?\r\n\r\n202\r\n00:10:12,395 --> 00:10:13,522\r\nYes, Joe.\r\n\r\n203\r\n00:10:13,546 --> 00:10:14,769\r\nGood. Then you won't\nbe needing your car.\r\n\r\n204\r\n00:10:14,793 --> 00:10:17,046\r\nMy car? Why, you...\r\n\r\n205\r\n00:10:17,622 --> 00:10:20,331\r\nIsn't he a bit of terrific?\r\n\r\n206\r\n00:10:24,479 --> 00:10:26,541\r\nWe coulda had three weeks\nin Florida, all expenses paid.\r\n\r\n207\r\n00:10:26,565 --> 00:10:28,171\r\nLyin' in the sun, palm trees, flyin' fish...\r\n\r\n208\r\n00:10:28,195 --> 00:10:30,617\r\nKnock it off, will ya?\r\n\r\n209\r\n00:10:31,192 --> 00:10:34,813\r\nPossible straight, possible nothing,\nand a pair of eights.\r\n\r\n210\r\n00:10:34,837 --> 00:10:36,011\r\nAll right, drop 'em, you guys.\r\n\r\n211\r\n00:10:36,035 --> 00:10:37,450\r\n- Drop what?\n- We came for a car