proceedings.\r\n\r\n908\r\n01:23:18,210 --> 01:23:21,550\r\n- Kobayashi.\r\n- New York faxed a copy of his testimony.\r\n\r\n909\r\n01:23:21,670 --> 01:23:24,050\r\n- He was a rat.\r\n- Yeah, a big fucking rat!\r\n\r\n910\r\n01:23:24,170 --> 01:23:27,140\r\nArturro was very opposed\r\nto returning to prison,\r\n\r\n911\r\n01:23:27,260 --> 01:23:31,100\r\nso much so that\r\nhe named close to 50 people.\r\n\r\n912\r\n01:23:31,220 --> 01:23:33,680\r\nGuess who he named in the finale?\r\n\r\n913\r\n01:23:34,600 --> 01:23:37,810\r\n- Keyser Söze.\r\n- There's more.\r\n\r\n914\r\n01:23:50,120 --> 01:23:54,250\r\nI'll tell you what I know.\r\nStop me when this sounds familiar.\r\n\r\n915\r\n01:23:55,750 --> 01:23:58,000\r\nThere was no dope on that boat.\r\n\r\n916\r\n01:24:03,880 --> 01:24:05,170\r\nArgh!\r\n\r\n917\r\n01:24:39,710 --> 01:24:44,300\r\n- You, stay quiet.\r\n- He's here. I know he's here.\r\n\r\n918\r\n01:24:45,000 --> 01:24:48,720\r\nThat's him. I'm telling you,\r\nthat's him. I know he's here!\r\n\r\n919\r\n01:24:50,390 --> 01:24:52,510\r\nYou can't understand. That's him.\r\n\r\n920\r\n01:24:52,680 --> 01:24:54,810\r\n- Shut up!\r\n- That's him. You hear me?\r\n\r\n921\r\n01:24:54,930 --> 01:24:58,230\r\nI'm telling you it's Keyser Söze!\r\n\r\n922\r\n01:26:56,510 --> 01:27:00,140\r\n- Where's Hockney?\r\n- I don't know. There's no coke!\r\n\r\n923\r\n01:27:00,260 --> 01:27:03,180\r\n- What?\r\n- You heard me, you dumb fuck! No coke!\r\n\r\n924\r\n01:27:03,310 --> 01:27:06,940\r\n- What the fuck do you mean?!\r\n- I've been in every fucking room!\r\n\r\n925\r\n01:27:07,060 --> 01:27:11,070\r\n- There's gotta be coke!\r\n- There is nothing! Nothing!\r\n\r\n926\r\n01:27:11,190 --> 01:27:12,820\r\nDon't fuck with me.\r\n\r\n927\r\n01:27:12,940 --> 01:27:16,860\r\nThere is no... fucking... coke!\r\n\r\n928\r\n01:27:27,790 --> 01:27:29,840\r\nI'm outta here.\r\n\r\n929\r\n01:28:10,460 --> 01:28:12,500\r\nI told them nothing.\r\n\r\n930\r\n01:28:13,380 --> 01:28:15,210\r\nI swear.\r\n\r\n931\r\n01:28:15,340 --> 01:28:17,800\r\nI told them nothing. Please.\r\n\r\n932\r\n01:29:04,220 --> 01:29:06,890\r\nMcManus, what the fuck is goin' on?\r\n\r\n933\r\n01:29:09,770 --> 01:29:11,810\r\nThe strangest thing.\r\n\r\n934\r\n01:30:06,280 --> 01:30:09,370\r\nYour statement says you saw a man\r\nin a suit with a slim build.\r\n\r\n935\r\n01:30:09,500 --> 01:30:12,920\r\n- Wait a minute.\r\n- Are you saying you saw Keyser Söze?\r\n\r\n936\r\n01:30:13,040 --> 01:30:16,590\r\n- You said you didn't know who it was.\r\n- There was dope on that boat.\r\n\r\n937\r\n01:30:16,710 --> 01:30:18,340\r\n- Stop stallin'.\r\n- I'm not!\r\n\r\n938\r\n01:30:18,460 --> 01:30:22,590\r\n- You know what I'm gettin' at!\r\n- Hey! I got immunity. I won't take this!\r\n\r\n939\r\n01:30:22,720 --> 01:30:25,470\r\nYou know... You know\r\nwhat I'm gettin' at, Verbal!\r\n\r\n940\r\n01:30:25,600 --> 01:30:27,930\r\n- I don't know!\r\n- Yes, you do! The truth!\r\n\r\n941\r\n01:30:28,060 --> 01:30:30,520\r\nTry to tell me\r\nyou saw someone kill Keaton.\r\n\r\n942\r\n01:30:30,640 --> 01:30:32,520\r\n- I did.\r\n- You're lying to me!\r\n\r\n943\r\n01:30:32,640 --> 01:30:35,480\r\n- I am not!\r\n- You've known this whole fuckin' time!\r\n\r\n944\r\n01:30:35,610 --> 01:30:39,280\r\nI don't know what you're saying.\r\nI did see Keaton get shot, I swear.\r\n\r\n945\r\n01:30:39,400 --> 01:30:43,320\r\nThen why didn't you help him?\r\nYou had a gun. He was your friend!\r\n\r\n946\r\n01:30:47,910 --> 01:30:51,580\r\nBecause I was afraid. OK?\r\n\r\n947\r\n01:30:51,910 --> 01:30:54,170\r\n- Afraid.\r\n- Afraid of what?\r\n\r\n948\r\n01:30:55,750 --> 01:30:58,090\r\n- I knew it was Keyser Söze.\r\n- But Keaton...\r\n\r\n949\r\n01:30:58,210 --> 01:31:01,970\r\nIt was Keyser Söze, Agent Kujan.\r\nI mean, the devil himself.\r\n\r\n950\r\n01:31:03,170 --> 01:31:05,640\r\nHow do you shoot the devil in the back?\r\n\r\n951\r\n01:31:10,350 --> 01:31:12,520\r\nWhat if you miss?\r\n\r\n952\r\n01:31:16,810 --> 01:31:19,190\r\nAll right. Let's get back to the pier.\r\n\r\n953\r\n01:32:42,520 --> 01:32:45,820\r\n- Arturro Marquez. Ever hear of him?\r\n- What? No.\r\n\r\n954\r\n01:32:45,940 --> 01:32:48,820\r\nHe was a stool pigeon\r\nfor the Justice Department.\r\n\r\n955\r\n01:32:48,950 --> 01:32:52,240\r\nHe swore out a statement\r\nsaying that he had seen\r\n\r\n956\r\n01:32:52,370 --> 01:32:56,370\r\nand could positively identify\r\none Keyser Söze.\r\n\r\n957\r\n01:32:56,500 --> 01:33:00,120\r\n\"He had\r\nintimate knowledge of his businesses,\r\n\r\n958\r\n01:33:00,250 --> 01:33:04,250\r\nincluding but not exclusive\r\nto drug-trafficking and murder.\"\r\n\r\n959\r\n01:33:04,380 --> 01:33:05,960\r\nI never heard of him.\r\n\r\n960\r\n01:33:06,090 --> 01:33:08,760\r\nHis people were selling him\r\nto a gang of Hungarians.\r\n\r\n961\r\n01:33:08,880 --> 01:33:12,470\r\nMost likely the same Hungarians\r\nSöze all but wiped out back in Turkey.\r\n\r\n962\r\n01:33:12,600 --> 01:33:14,640\r\nThe money wasn't there for dope.\r\n\r\n963\r\n01:33:14,760 --> 01:33:19,100\r\nThe Hungarians were gonna buy the one\r\nguy that could incriminate Keyser Söze.\r\n\r\n964\r\n01:33:19,230 --> 01:33:21,650\r\n- I said I never heard of him.\r\n- Keaton did.\r\n\r\n965\r\n01:33:21,770 --> 01:33:26,690\r\nEdie Finneran was Marquez's extradition\r\nadviser. She knew what he knew.\r\n\r\n966\r\n01:33:26,820 --> 01:33:31,030\r\n- I don't under...\r\n- There were no drugs. It was a hit.\r\n\r\n967\r\n01:33:31,160 --> 01:33:35,870\r\nA suicide mission to whack out the\r\none guy that could finger Keyser Söze.\r\n\r\n968\r\n01:33:35,990 --> 01:33:40,790\r\nSo Söze put some thieves to it, men he\r\nknew he could march into certain death.\r\n\r\n969\r\n01:33:40,920 --> 01:33:43,670\r\nYou're saying Söze\r\nsent us to kill someone?\r\n\r\n970\r\n01:33:44,670 --> 01:33:47,510\r\nKeaton did. Verbal,\r\nhe left you behind for a reason.\r\n\r\n971\r\n01:33:47,630 --> 01:33:49,590\r\nJust do what I tell you.\r\n\r\n972\r\n01:33:49,720 --> 01:33:54,720\r\nIf you all knew Söze'd find you anywhere,\r\nwhy did he give you the money to run?\r\n\r\n973\r\n01:33:54,850 --> 01:33:58,140\r\n- He could have used you on the boat.\r\n- He wanted me to live.\r\n\r\n974\r\n01:33:59,640 --> 01:34:02,270\r\nA one-time dirty cop\r\nwithout a loyalty in the world\r\n\r\n975\r\n01:34:02,400 --> 01:34:05,860\r\nfinds it in his heart\r\nto save a worthless rat cripple.\r\n\r\n976\r\n01:34:05,980 --> 01:34:08,320\r\nNo, sir. Why?\r\n\r\n977\r\n01:34:08,440 --> 01:34:11,860\r\n- Edie.\r\n- I don't buy the reform story for a minute.\r\n\r\n978\r\n01:34:11,990 --> 01:34:17,120\r\nEven if I did, I certainly don't believe\r\nhe would send you to protect her.\r\n\r\n979\r\n01:34:17,240 --> 01:34:19,290\r\nSo why?\r\n\r\n980\r\n01:34:20,830 --> 01:34:22,870\r\nBecause he was my friend.\r\n\r\n981\r\n01:34:23,000 --> 01:34:25,380\r\nNo, Verbal. He wasn't your friend.\r\n\r\n982\r\n01:34:25,500 --> 01:34:28,460\r\n- Keaton didn't have friends.\r\n- What are you doin' here?\r\n\r\n983\r\n01:34:28,590 --> 01:34:32,340\r\nHe saved you because\r\nhe wanted it that way. It was his will.\r\n\r\n984\r\n01:34:32,970 --> 01:34:35,550\r\n- Keaton was Keyser Söze.\r\n- No.\r\n\r\n985\r\n01:34:35,680 --> 01:34:39,140\r\nThe kind of man who could wrangle\r\nmen like Hockney and McManus.\r\n\r\n986\r\n01:34:39,270 --> 01:34:44,400\r\nThe kind of man who could engineer\r\na line-up through all his contacts at NYPD.\r\n\r\n987\r\n01:34:44,520 --> 01:34:47,820\r\nThe kind of man who\r\ncould've killed Edie Finneran!\r\n\r\n988\r\n01:34:52,200 --> 01:34:56,990\r\nShe was found yesterday at a hotel\r\nin Pennsylvania, shot twice in the head.\r\n\r\n989\r\n01:35:01,910 --> 01:35:04,790\r\nWhat do you think\r\nabout Keaton now, Verbal?\r\n\r\n990\r\n01:35:05,790 --> 01:35:07,000\r\nEdie?\r\n\r\n991\r\n01:35:07,130 --> 01:35:11,090\r\nHe used all of you to get him on that boat.\r\nHe couldn't get on alone.\r\n\r\n992\r\n01:35:11,210 --> 01:35:14,760\r\nHe had to pull the trigger himself\r\nto make sure he got his man.\r\n\r\n993\r\n01:35:14,880 --> 01:35:17,850\r\nThe one man that could identify him.\r\n\r\n994\r\n01:35:17,970 --> 01:35:19,810\r\nThis is all bullshit.\r\n\r\n995\r\n01:35:19,930 --> 01:35:21,980\r\nYou said you saw him die.\r\n\r\n996\r\n01:35:24,520 --> 01:35:27,770\r\nOr did you? You had to hide\r\nwhen you heard the police cars.\r\n\r\n997\r\n01:35:28,020 --> 01:35:30,610\r\nYou said you heard the shot\r\nbefore the fire.\r\n\r\n998\r\n01:35:30,730 --> 01:35:34,570\r\n- But you didn't see him die.\r\n- I knew him. He would never...\r\n\r\n999\r\n01:35:34,700 --> 01:35:38,450\r\nHe programmed you to tell us\r\njust what he wanted you to.\r\n\r\n1000\r\n01:35:38,620 --> 01:35:40,950\r\nHe knew we were close,\r\nyou said it yourself.\r\n\r\n1001\r\n01:35:41,080 --> 01:35:45,250\r\nWhere was the political pressure\r\ncoming from? It was Keaton.\r\n\r\n1002\r\n01:35:45,370 --> 01:35:47,210\r\nImmunity was your reward.\r\n\r\n1003\r\n01:35:47,330 --> 01:35:49,170\r\nBut why me?\r\n\r\n1004\r\n01:35:49,290 --> 01:35:54,050\r\nWhy not Fenster, McManus or Hockney?\r\nI'm stupid. I'm a cripple. Why me?\r\n\r\n1005\r\n01:35:54,170 --> 01:35:58,050\r\nBecause you're a cripple, Verbal.\r\nBecause you're stupid.\r\n\r\n1006\r\n01:35:58,180 --> 01:36:00,220\r\nBecause you're weaker than them.\r\n\r\n1007\r\n01:36:04,390 --> 01:36:08,310\r\nIf he's dead, if what you say is true,\r\n\r\n1008\r\n01:36:08,440 --> 01:36:10,480\r\nthen it won't matter.\r\n\r\n1009\r\n01:36:11,570 --> 01:36:15,900\r\nIt was his idea to hit the taxi service\r\nin New York, wasn't it? Tell me the truth.\r\n\r\n1010\r\n01:36:16,030 --> 01:36:19,030\r\nIt was all Keaton.\r\n\r\n1011\r\n01:36:19,160 --> 01:36:22,040\r\nWe followed him from the beginning.\r\n\r\n1012\r\n01:36:23,370 --> 01:36:27,460\r\nI didn't know. I saw him die.\r\n\r\n1013\r\n01:36:27,580 --> 01:36:31,250\r\nI believe he's dead. Oh, Christ!\r\n\r\n1014\r\n01:36:32,000 --> 01:36:34,460\r\nYou're not safe on your own.\r\n\r\n1015\r\n01:36:37,840 --> 01:36:40,720\r\n- You think he's...\r\n- Keyser Söze?\r\n\r\n1016\r\n01:36:41,600 --> 01:36:43,640\r\nI don't know, Verbal.\r\n\r\n1017\r\n01:36:44,720 --> 01:36:48,480\r\nKeyser Söze's a shield.\r\nOr, like you said, a spook story.\r\n\r\n1018\r\n01:36:49,810 --> 01:36:54,110\r\nBut I know Keaton, and someone\r\nis out there pulling strings for you.\r\n\r\n1019\r\n01:36:54,230 --> 01:36:57,740\r\n- Stay and let us protect you.\r\n- No way. I'm not bait. I post today.\r\n\r\n1020\r\n01:36:57,860 --> 01:36:59,700\r\nYou posted 20 minutes ago.\r\n\r\n1021\r\n01:36:59,820 --> 01:37:03,410\r\nCaptain Leo wants you out of here ASAP,\r\nunless you turn state's.\r\n\r\n1022\r\n01:37:03,530 --> 01:37:05,240\r\nI'll take my chances.\r\n\r\n1023\r\n01:37:05,370 --> 01:37:09,120\r\nIf someone wants to get you,\r\nthey're gonna get you out there.\r\n\r\n1024\r\n01:37:09,290 --> 01:37:12,670\r\nTurn state's evidence.\r\nYou might never see trial.\r\n\r\n1025\r\n01:37:12,790 --> 01:37:14,840\r\nMaybe so.\r\n\r\n1026\r\n01:37:15,590 --> 01:37:18,050\r\nBut I'm not a rat, Agent Kujan.\r\n\r\n1027\r\n01:37:34,270 --> 01:37:36,320\r\nFuckin' cops.\r\n\r\n1028\r\n01:38:00,300 --> 01:38:02,840\r\nExcuse me. Can I use your fax machine?\r\n\r\n1029\r\n01:38:06,890 --> 01:38:09,350\r\nYou'll have to sign for these, Mr Kint.\r\n\r\n1030\r\n01:38:11,690 --> 01:38:15,820\r\nOne watch, gold.\r\nOne cigarette lighter, gold.\r\n\r\n1031\r\n01:38:16,730 --> 01:38:18,820\r\nOne pack of cigarettes. Thank you.\r\n\r\n1032\r\n01:38:19,400 --> 01:38:21,650\r\nWe've still got nothing, Dave.\r\n\r\n1033\r\n01:38:21,780 --> 01:38:24,120\r\nI know what I wanted\r\nto know about Keaton.\r\n\r\n1034\r\n01:38:24,240 --> 01:38:26,080\r\nWhich is nothing.\r\n\r\n1035\r\n01:38:26,200 --> 01:38:29,750\r\nNo matter. He'll have\r\nto know how close we came.\r\n\r\n1036\r\n01:38:30,410 --> 01:38:33,250\r\nKeyser Söze or no Keyser Söze,\r\n\r\n1037\r\n01:38:33,370 --> 01:38:36,590\r\nif Keaton is alive,\r\nhe's not coming up again.\r\n\r\n1038\r\n01:38:36,710 --> 01:38:38,840\r\nI'll find him.\r\n\r\n1039\r\n01:38:38,960 --> 01:38:41,010\r\nWaste of time.\r\n\r\n1040\r\n01:38:43,130 --> 01:38:46,050\r\nA rumour's not\r\na rumour that doesn't die.\r\n\r\n1041\r\n01:38:46,180 --> 01:38:49,180\r\n- What?\r\n- Nothin'.\r\n\r\n1042\r\n01:38:51,270 --> 01:38:56,310\r\n- Man, you're a slob.\r\n- Yeah, but it all has a system, Dave.\r\n\r\n1043\r\n01:38:56,480 --> 01:39:01,110\r\nIt all makes sense when you look at\r\nit right. You gotta stand back from it.\r\n\r\n1044\r\n01:39:02,150 --> 01:39:05,820\r\nYou wanna see a real horror show,\r\nyou should see my garage.\r\n\r\n1045\r\n01:39:42,440 --> 01:39:44,490\r\nConvince me.\r\n\r\n1046\r\n01:39:44,610 --> 01:39:48,780\r\nWhen I was in that barbershop quartet in\r\nSkokie. Where's your head, Agent Kujan?\r\n\r\n1047\r\n01:39:48,910 --> 01:39:52,700\r\n- We need to think back.\r\n- You've heard many tales.\r\n\r\n1048\r\n01:39:52,830 --> 01:39:55,830\r\n- Bricks Marlin.\r\n- I wanna hear your story.\r\n\r\n1049\r\n01:39:55,960 --> 01:40:00,420\r\nIt's all there. Some guy\r\nin California, his name is Redfoot.\r\n\r\n1050\r\n01:40:00,550 --> 01:40:04,170\r\n- A gift from Mr Söze.\r\n- What about Redfoot?\r\n\r\n1051\r\n01:40:04,300 --> 01:40:09,180\r\n- Mr Redfoot knew nothing.\r\n- Big, fat guy. I mean, orca fat.\r\n\r\n1052\r\n01:40:09,300 --> 01:40:11,930\r\nThere was a lawyer. Kobayashi.\r\n\r\n1053\r\n01:40:13,220 --> 01:40:16,520\r\nWhen I was picking beans in Guatemala,\r\nwe'd make fresh coffee.\r\n\r\n1054\r\n01:40:16,640 --> 01:40:20,900\r\n- You thought he was a good man.\r\n- I know he was good.\r\n\r\n1055\r\n01:40:22,110 --> 01:40:26,490\r\n- Tell me every last detail.\r\n- How do you shoot the devil?\r\n\r\n1056\r\n01:40:26,610 --> 01:40:32,120\r\n- He's protected by the Prince of...\r\n- What's your story?\r\n\r\n1057\r\n01:40:32,240 --> 01:40:34,410\r\n- There was a lawyer.\r\n- What lawyer, Verbal?\r\n\r\n1058\r\n01:40:34,540 --> 01:40:37,370\r\n- I am Mr Kobayashi.\r\n- Kobayashi. Kobayashi.\r\n\r\n1059\r\n01:40:37,500 --> 01:40:40,540\r\n- Tell me every last detail.\r\n- I work for Keyser Söze.\r\n\r\n1060\r\n01:40:40,670 --> 01:40:43,050\r\nConvince me. Convince me.\r\n\r\n1061\r\n01:40:57,890 --> 01:41:02,650\r\nEvery creep that works the street for a\r\nliving will know the name of Verbal Kint.\r\n\r\n1062\r\n01:41:03,190 --> 01:41:04,820\r\nThe cripple, did you see him?!\r\n\r\n1063\r\n01:41:04,940 --> 01:41:07,950\r\n- The cripple! Which way did he go?\r\n- That way.\r\n\r\n1064\r\n01:41:08,070 --> 01:41:10,530\r\nI know you know something.\r\n\r\n1065\r\n01:41:10,660 --> 01:41:14,330\r\nI'm smarter than you and\r\nI'm gonna find out what I wanna know.\r\n\r\n1066\r\n01:41:14,450 --> 01:41:18,790\r\n- To a cop, the explanation's simple.\r\n- You know what I'm gettin' at! The truth!\r\n\r\n1067\r\n01:41:18,920 --> 01:41:23,090\r\n- ...no arch criminal behind it all.\r\n- Somebody with power.\r\n\r\n1068\r\n01:41:23,210 --> 01:41:26,800\r\n- Keyser Söze!\r\n- Who's Keyser Söze?\r\n\r\n1069\r\n01:41:26,920 --> 01:41:32,720\r\nYou think a guy like that comes this close\r\nto getting caught and sticks his head out?\r\n\r\n1070\r\n01:41:32,850 --> 01:41:35,930\r\nBecause you're stupid, Verbal.\r\nBecause you're a cripple.\r\n\r\n1071\r\n01:41:36,060 --> 01:41:39,520\r\n- Who's the gimp?\r\n- You've known the whole fuckin' time!\r\n\r\n1072\r\n01:41:39,640 --> 01:41:42,650\r\n- Who's Keyser Söze?\r\n- Who's Keyser Söze?\r\n\r\n1073\r\n01:41:42,770 --> 01:41:47,440\r\n- I'm sure Keaton is dead.\r\n- I can't feel my legs, Keyser.\r\n\r\n1074\r\n01:41:47,570 --> 01:41:51,030\r\nFirst thing I learnt on the job\r\nwas how to spot a murderer.\r\n\r\n1075\r\n01:41:51,160 --> 01:41:55,160\r\nThey tell me you got the cripple\r\nfrom New York. He mention Keyser Söze?\r\n\r\n1076\r\n01:41:55,280 --> 01:41:56,370\r\nWho?\r\n\r\n1077\r\n01:41:56,490 --> 01:42:01,460\r\nAfter that... my guess is\r\nyou'll never hear from him again.\r\n\r\n1078\r\n01:42:22,190 --> 01:42:27,530\r\nThe greatest trick the devil ever pulled\r\nwas convincing the world he didn't exist.\r\n\r\n1079\r\n01:42:29,570 --> 01:42:31,860\r\nAnd like that...\r\n\r\n1080\r\n01:42:31,990 --> 01:42:34,030\r\nhe's gone.\r\n\r\n","markerStore":{"nextMarkerId":367,"markersById":{"0":{"range":{"start":{"row":0,"column":0},"end":{"row":0,"column":0}},"properties":{"type":"selection","editorId":136,"goalScreenRange":null},"reversed":false,"tailed":false,"valid":true,"invalidate":"never","maintainHistory":true}},"version":2},"history":{"version":3,"nextCheckpointId":1,"undoStack":[],"redoStack":[]},"encoding":"utf8","filePath":"/Users/joegesualdo/.Trash/The.Usual.Suspects.1995.1080p.BluRay.x264.AC3-ETRG.srt 3.08.07 PM","digestWhenLastPersisted":"c670f7304f69ccfd209f54cceb8e9ffbf932b44f","preferredLineEnding":null,"deserializer":"TextBuffer","version":2},{"load":true,"text":"1\r\n00:01:38,560 --> 00:01:44,749\r\n<i>On November 1, 1959, the population</i>\r\n<i>of New York City was 8,042, 783.</i>\r\n\r\n2\r\n00:01:45,480 --> 00:01:49,871\r\n<i>If you laid them all end to end, figuring</i>\r\n<i>an average height of 5 feet 6 1/2 inches...</i>\r\n\r\n3\r\n00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:53,879\r\n<i>... they would reach from Times Square</i>\r\n<i>to the outskirts of Karachi, Pakistan.</i>\r\n\r\n4\r\n00:01:54,000 --> 00:01:58,232\r\n<i>I know facts like this because I work for</i>\r\n<i>an insurance company, Consolidated Life.</i>\r\n\r\n5\r\n00:01:58,360 --> 00:02:00,794\r\n<i>We're one of the top five companies</i>\r\n<i>in the country.</i>\r\n\r\n6\r\n00:02:00,920 --> 00:02:04,549\r\n<i>Our home office has 31,259 employees...</i>\r\n\r\n7\r\n00:02:04,680 --> 00:02:08,832\r\n<i>... which is more than the entire population</i>\r\n<i>of, uh... Natchez, Mississippi.</i>\r\n\r\n8\r\n00:02:08,960 --> 00:02:11,838\r\n<i>I work on the 19th floor.</i>\r\n<i>Ordinary Policy Department...</i>\r\n\r\n9\r\n00:02:11,960 --> 00:02:15,919\r\n<i>... Premium Accounting Division,</i>\r\n<i>Section W, desk number 861.</i>\r\n\r\n10\r\n00:02:16,440 --> 00:02:20,877\r\n<i>My name is CC Baxter... C for Calvin, C for</i>\r\n<i>Clifford. But most people call me Bud.</i>\r\n\r\n11\r\n00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:25,949\r\n<i>I've worked here three years, ten months,</i>\r\n<i>and my take-home pay is $94.70 a week.</i>\r\n\r\n12\r\n00:02:35,760 --> 00:02:38,832\r\n<i>The hours in our department</i>\r\n<i>are 8.50 to 5.20.</i>\r\n\r\n13\r\n00:02:43,600 --> 00:02:48,355\r\n<i>They're staggered by floor so 16 elevators</i>\r\n<i>can handle the 31,259 employees...</i>\r\n\r\n14\r\n00:02:48,480 --> 00:02:50,835\r\n<i>... without a serious traffic jam.</i>\r\n\r\n15\r\n00:02:50,960 --> 00:02:55,909\r\n<i>As for myself, I very often stay on at the</i>\r\n<i>office and work for an extra hour or two...</i>\r\n\r\n16\r\n00:02:56,040 --> 00:02:58,031\r\n<i>... especially when the weather is bad.</i>\r\n\r\n17\r\n00:02:58,160 --> 00:03:01,596\r\n<i>It's not that I'm overly ambitious.</i>\r\n<i>It's just a way of killing time...</i>\r\n\r\n18\r\n00:03:01,720 --> 00:03:04,314\r\n<i>... until it's all right for me to go home.</i>\r\n\r\n19\r\n00:03:04,440 --> 00:03:07,750\r\n<i>You see, I have this little problem</i>\r\n<i>with my apartment.</i>\r\n\r\n20\r\n00:03:09,280 --> 00:03:12,397\r\n<i>I live in the West 60s,</i>\r\n<i>just half a block from Central Park.</i>\r\n\r\n21\r\n00:03:12,520 --> 00:03:15,557\r\n<i>My rent is $85 a month.</i>\r\n<i>It used to be $80 until last July...</i>\r\n\r\n22\r\n00:03:15,680 --> 00:03:19,434\r\n<i>... when Mrs Lieberman, the landlady,</i>\r\n<i>put in a second-hand air conditioner.</i>\r\n\r\n23\r\n00:03:19,560 --> 00:03:24,998\r\n<i>It's a real nice apartment. Nothing fancy,</i>\r\n<i>but kind of cosy. Just right for a bachelor.</i>\r\n\r\n24\r\n00:03:25,120 --> 00:03:28,430\r\n<i>The only problem is</i>\r\n<i>I can't always get in when I want to.</i>\r\n\r\n25\r\n00:03:41,640 --> 00:03:44,837\r\nCut it out, Sylvia.\r\nWe've gotta get out of here.\r\n\r\n26\r\n00:03:44,960 --> 00:03:47,872\r\nWhat's the panic?\r\nI'm gonna have another martini.\r\n\r\n27\r\n00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:50,070\r\nPlease, Sylvia. It's a quarter of nine.\r\n\r\n28\r\n00:03:50,200 --> 00:03:53,397\r\nFirst you can't wait to get me here\r\nand then it's rush, rush, rush.\r\n\r\n29\r\n00:03:53,520 --> 00:03:56,592\r\n- Makes a person feel cheap.\r\n- Sweetie, it's not that.\r\n\r\n30\r\n00:03:56,720 --> 00:03:59,393\r\nBut I promised the guy\r\nI'd be outta here by eight.\r\n\r\n31\r\n00:03:59,520 --> 00:04:04,913\r\n- What guy? Whose apartment is this?\r\n- Some schnook that works in the office.\r\n\r\n32\r\n00:04:17,840 --> 00:04:20,149\r\n- Good evening, Mr Baxter.\r\n- Mrs Lieberman.\r\n\r\n33\r\n00:04:20,280 --> 00:04:25,035\r\nSome weather we're having. Must be from\r\nall that <i>meshugaas</i> at Cape Canaveral.\r\n\r\n34\r\n00:04:26,320 --> 00:04:30,836\r\n- You're locked out of your apartment?\r\n- No, no. Just waiting for a friend.\r\n\r\n35\r\n00:04:31,360 --> 00:04:34,591\r\n- Good night, Mrs Lieberman.\r\n- Good night, Mr Baxter.\r\n\r\n36\r\n00:04:51,800 --> 00:04:54,360\r\n- Where do you live?\r\n- I told you. With my mother.\r\n\r\n37\r\n00:04:54,480 --> 00:04:57,552\r\n- Where does <i>she</i> live?\r\n- 179th Street, in the Bronx.\r\n\r\n38\r\n00:04:57,680 --> 00:05:02,470\r\n- All right. I'll take you to the subway.\r\n- Like hell you will! You'll buy me a cab.\r\n\r\n39\r\n00:05:02,600 --> 00:05:06,354\r\n- Why do all you dames live in the Bronx?\r\n- You bring other girls up here?\r\n\r\n40\r\n00:05:06,480 --> 00:05:09,233\r\nCertainly not. I'm a happily married man.\r\n\r\n41\r\n00:05:46,960 --> 00:05:49,952\r\n- Hello there, Mrs Dreyfuss.\r\n- Something's the matter?\r\n\r\n42\r\n00:05:50,080 --> 00:05:53,993\r\nUh, no. I... seem to have\r\ndropped my key. Ah, here it is.\r\n\r\n43\r\n00:05:54,120 --> 00:05:56,509\r\nSuch a racket I heard in your place.\r\n\r\n44\r\n00:05:56,640 --> 00:05:58,676\r\nMaybe you had burglars?\r\n\r\n45\r\n00:05:58,800 --> 00:06:03,078\r\nDon't worry about that. There's nothing in\r\nhere anybody'd wanna steal. Good night.\r\n\r\n46\r\n00:06:40,480 --> 00:06:44,837\r\nSorry to bother you, Buddy-boy,\r\nbut the little lady forgot her galoshes.\r\n\r\n47\r\n00:06:44,960 --> 00:06:48,316\r\nMr Kirkeby, you were supposed\r\nto be outta here by eight.\r\n\r\n48\r\n00:06:48,440 --> 00:06:52,831\r\nI know, but those things don't always\r\nrun on schedule like a Greyhound bus.\r\n\r\n49\r\n00:06:52,960 --> 00:06:55,520\r\nI don't mind in the summer,\r\nbut on a rainy night...\r\n\r\n50\r\n00:06:55,640 --> 00:06:58,200\r\n- I haven't had any dinner yet.\r\n- Sure, sure.\r\n\r\n51\r\n00:06:58,320 --> 00:06:59,320\r\nOh!\r\n\r\n52\r\n00:07:00,640 --> 00:07:03,677\r\nI put in a good word for you\r\nwith Sheldrake in Personnel.\r\n\r\n53\r\n00:07:03,800 --> 00:07:05,313\r\n- Mr Sheldrake?\r\n- That's right.\r\n\r\n54\r\n00:07:05,440 --> 00:07:09,228\r\nWe discussed manpower promotionwise.\r\nI told him you're a bright boy.\r\n\r\n55\r\n00:07:09,360 --> 00:07:13,319\r\nThey're always on the lookout for\r\nyoung executives. You're on your way up.\r\n\r\n56\r\n00:07:13,440 --> 00:07:17,149\r\n- And you're also out of liquor.\r\n- Mr Eichelberger, Mortgage and Loans...\r\n\r\n57\r\n00:07:17,280 --> 00:07:21,558\r\n...last night he had a Halloween party.\r\n- Lay in some vodka and vermouth for me.\r\n\r\n58\r\n00:07:21,680 --> 00:07:25,798\r\n- You still owe me for the last two bottles.\r\n- I'll pay you on Friday.\r\n\r\n59\r\n00:07:25,920 --> 00:07:30,948\r\nOh, and whatever happened to those little\r\ncheese crackers you used to have?\r\n\r\n60\r\n00:07:33,080 --> 00:07:35,036\r\nCheese crackers?\r\n\r\n61\r\n00:08:11,840 --> 00:08:13,240\r\nCheers.\r\n\r\n62\r\n00:08:29,480 --> 00:08:31,948\r\n- Good evening, Baxter.\r\n- Hi, Doc. Had a late call?\r\n\r\n63\r\n00:08:32,080 --> 00:08:36,551\r\nYeah. Some clown at Schrafft's ate\r\na club sandwich - including the toothpick.\r\n\r\n64\r\n00:08:38,520 --> 00:08:41,080\r\n- Well, good night, Doc.\r\n- Say, Baxter.\r\n\r\n65\r\n00:08:41,200 --> 00:08:44,875\r\nThe way you're beltin' that stuff,\r\nyou must have cast-iron kidneys.\r\n\r\n66\r\n00:08:45,000 --> 00:08:49,039\r\nThat's not me. Just once in a while\r\nI have a few people in for a drink.\r\n\r\n67\r\n00:08:49,160 --> 00:08:52,118\r\nAs a matter of fact, you must be\r\nan iron man all around.\r\n\r\n68\r\n00:08:52,240 --> 00:08:55,391\r\nFrom what I hear through the walls,\r\nyou're at it every night.\r\n\r\n69\r\n00:08:55,520 --> 00:08:59,798\r\n- I'm sorry if it gets noisy.\r\n- And sometimes there's a double-header.\r\n\r\n70\r\n00:09:00,520 --> 00:09:03,796\r\n- A <i>nebbish</i> like you.\r\n- Yeah. Well, I'll see you, Doc.\r\n\r\n71\r\n00:09:03,920 --> 00:09:07,515\r\nYou know, I'm doing some research\r\nat the Columbia Medical Center.\r\n\r\n72\r\n00:09:07,640 --> 00:09:09,835\r\n- Could you do us a favour?\r\n- Me?\r\n\r\n73\r\n00:09:09,960 --> 00:09:13,635\r\nWhen you make out your will -\r\nand the way you're going, you should -\r\n\r\n74\r\n00:09:13,760 --> 00:09:17,673\r\nwould you mind leaving\r\nyour body to the university?\r\n\r\n75\r\n00:09:17,800 --> 00:09:21,918\r\nMy body? I'm afraid you guys'd\r\nbe disappointed. Good night, Doc.\r\n\r\n76\r\n00:09:23,240 --> 00:09:25,196\r\nSlow down, kid.\r\n\r\n77\r\n00:10:02,160 --> 00:10:04,116\r\nOh, for heaven...\r\n\r\n78\r\n00:10:11,280 --> 00:10:15,717\r\n<i>From the world's greatest library</i>\r\n<i>of film classics, we proudly present...</i>\r\n\r\n79\r\n00:10:15,840 --> 00:10:18,149\r\n<i>... Greta Garbo, John Barrymore...</i>\r\n\r\n80\r\n00:10:18,280 --> 00:10:22,239\r\n<i>... Joan Crawford, Wallace Beery</i>\r\n<i>and Lionel Barrymore...</i>\r\n\r\n81\r\n00:10:22,360 --> 00:10:24,999\r\n<i>... in \"Grand Hotel\".</i>\r\n\r\n82\r\n00:10:25,760 --> 00:10:28,194\r\n<i>But first, a word from our sponsor.</i>\r\n\r\n83\r\n00:10:28,320 --> 00:10:32,472\r\n<i>If you smoke the modern way,</i>\r\n<i>don't be fooled by phoney filter claims.</i>\r\n\r\n84\r\n00:11:02,360 --> 00:11:05,033\r\n<i>And now, \"Grand Hotel\"...</i>\r\n\r\n85\r\n00:11:05,160 --> 00:11:07,833\r\n<i>... starring Greta Garbo, John Barrymore...</i>\r\n\r\n86\r\n00:11:07,960 --> 00:11:11,350\r\n<i>... Joan Crawford, Wallace Beery</i>\r\n<i>and Lionel Barrymore.</i>\r\n\r\n87\r\n00:11:12,040 --> 00:11:15,635\r\n<i>But first, a word</i>\r\n<i>from our alternate sponsor.</i>\r\n\r\n88\r\n00:11:15,760 --> 00:11:19,275\r\n<i>Friends, do you have wobbly dentures?</i>\r\n\r\n89\r\n00:11:44,320 --> 00:11:46,038\r\n- Hello.\r\n- Hiya, Buddy-boy.\r\n\r\n90\r\n00:11:46,160 --> 00:11:49,835\r\nI'm in this bar on 61st Street\r\nand I figured I'd give you a little buzz.\r\n\r\n91\r\n00:11:49,960 --> 00:11:52,394\r\nThat's very nice of you but... who is this?\r\n\r\n92\r\n00:11:52,520 --> 00:11:54,909\r\nDobisch. Joe Dobisch, in Administration.\r\n\r\n93\r\n00:11:55,040 --> 00:11:58,669\r\n- Oh, yeah. I didn't recognise your voice.\r\n- That's OK, Buddy-boy.\r\n\r\n94\r\n00:11:58,800 --> 00:12:03,157\r\nLike I was saying, I'm in this joint\r\non 61st and I think I got lucky.\r\n\r\n95\r\n00:12:04,320 --> 00:12:08,154\r\nI'm sorry, Mr Dobisch. I like to help\r\nyou fellas out, but it's sort of late.\r\n\r\n96\r\n00:12:08,280 --> 00:12:12,432\r\n- Why don't we make it some other time?\r\n- Listen, kid. I can't pass this up.\r\n\r\n97\r\n00:12:12,560 --> 00:12:15,154\r\nShe looks like Marilyn Monroe.\r\n\r\n98\r\n00:12:15,280 --> 00:12:19,353\r\nI'm already in bed. And I took a sleeping\r\npill. So I'm afraid the answer is no.\r\n\r\n99\r\n00:12:19,880 --> 00:12:23,839\r\nWe're doing the monthly efficiency rating.\r\nI'm putting you in the top ten.\r\n\r\n100\r\n00:12:23,960 --> 00:12:26,110\r\nYou don't wanna\r\nlouse yourself up, do you?\r\n\r\n101\r\n00:12:26,240 --> 00:12:30,791\r\nNo. But how can I be efficient in the\r\noffice if I don't get enough sleep at night?\r\n\r\n102\r\n00:12:30,920 --> 00:12:34,879\r\nIt's only eleven, and I just\r\nwant the place for 45 minutes.\r\n\r\n103\r\n00:12:37,040 --> 00:12:39,838\r\nI'm getting lonely.\r\nWho are you talking to, anyway?\r\n\r\n104\r\n00:12:39,960 --> 00:12:43,794\r\n- My mother.\r\n- Oh, that's sweet. That's real sweet.\r\n\r\n105\r\n00:12:44,400 --> 00:12:45,400\r\nOoh!\r\n\r\n106\r\n00:12:47,280 --> 00:12:49,999\r\nMake it 30 minutes.\r\nWhat do you say, Bud, huh?\r\n\r\n107\r\n00:12:50,560 --> 00:12:53,757\r\nI'm all out of liquor,\r\nthere's no clean glasses...\r\n\r\n108\r\n00:12:53,880 --> 00:12:57,395\r\n- There's no cheese crackers. No nothin'.\r\n- Let me worry about that.\r\n\r\n109\r\n00:12:57,520 --> 00:13:00,239\r\nJust leave the key under the mat\r\nand clear out.\r\n\r\n110\r\n00:13:00,360 --> 00:13:02,316\r\nYes, Mr Dobisch.\r\n\r\n111\r\n00:13:03,240 --> 00:13:05,754\r\nAnything you say, Mr Dobisch\r\n\r\n112\r\n00:13:06,560 --> 00:13:10,155\r\nNo trouble at all, Mr Dobisch\r\nBe my guest!\r\n\r\n113\r\n00:13:11,080 --> 00:13:13,833\r\nWe never close at Buddy-boy's.\r\n\r\n114\r\n00:13:17,440 --> 00:13:19,396\r\n\"Looks like Marilyn Monroe\"\r\n\r\n115\r\n00:14:01,080 --> 00:14:03,878\r\n- This the place?\r\n- Yeah.\r\n\r\n116\r\n00:14:04,000 --> 00:14:05,877\r\n- How much?\r\n- 70 cents.\r\n\r\n117\r\n00:14:06,000 --> 00:14:07,956\r\nGet the money, will you?\r\n\r\n118\r\n00:14:09,600 --> 00:14:11,556\r\nWatch those stingers!\r\n\r\n119\r\n00:14:12,880 --> 00:14:14,836\r\n- Give him a buck.\r\n- Thanks, lady.\r\n\r\n120\r\n00:14:16,680 --> 00:14:18,636\r\nPut it back, honey!\r\n\r\n121\r\n00:14:20,520 --> 00:14:22,320\r\nAttagirl.\r\n\r\n122\r\n00:14:22,520 --> 00:14:25,557\r\n- Are you sure this is a good idea?\r\n- Can't think of a better one.\r\n\r\n123\r\n00:14:25,680 --> 00:14:27,875\r\nBarging in on your mother so late at night.\r\n\r\n124\r\n00:14:28,000 --> 00:14:32,437\r\nDon't worry about the old lady. One\r\nsquawk from her and she's out of a job.\r\n\r\n125\r\n00:14:47,880 --> 00:14:49,836\r\nGet the key, will you?\r\n\r\n126\r\n00:14:50,480 --> 00:14:52,675\r\nNot there! Under the mat.\r\n\r\n127\r\n00:14:52,800 --> 00:14:55,394\r\n- Under the mat?\r\n- Yeah. Come on.\r\n\r\n128\r\n00:14:56,120 --> 00:14:58,475\r\nOpen up. We haven't got all night.\r\n\r\n129\r\n00:15:01,760 --> 00:15:05,116\r\n- This is your mother's apartment?\r\n- That's right.\r\n\r\n130\r\n00:15:18,320 --> 00:15:20,709\r\nMildred! He's at it again!\r\n\r\n131\r\n00:16:08,840 --> 00:16:11,149\r\n- Morning, Mr Kirkeby.\r\n- How are you, Baxter?\r\n\r\n132\r\n00:16:11,280 --> 00:16:15,034\r\n- They keeping you busy these days?\r\n- Yes, sir. They are indeed.\r\n\r\n133\r\n00:16:15,160 --> 00:16:18,675\r\nGood morning, Mr Kessel, Miss Robinson,\r\nMr Williams, Miss Livingston.\r\n\r\n134\r\n00:16:18,800 --> 00:16:21,519\r\nGood morning, Mr McKellway,\r\nMrs Schubert, Mr Davis.\r\n\r\n135\r\n00:16:21,640 --> 00:16:24,234\r\nGood morning, Mr Kirkeby.\r\nGood morning, Mr Baxter.\r\n\r\n136\r\n00:16:24,360 --> 00:16:27,079\r\n- Morning, Miss Kubelik.\r\n- That's all. Take it away.\r\n\r\n137\r\n00:16:27,200 --> 00:16:29,555\r\nWatch the door, please. Blasting off.\r\n\r\n138\r\n00:16:32,920 --> 00:16:36,196\r\n- What did you do to your hair?\r\n- It made me nervous so I chopped it off.\r\n\r\n139\r\n00:16:36,320 --> 00:16:39,471\r\n- Big mistake, huh?\r\n- No. I sort of like it.\r\n\r\n140\r\n00:16:39,600 --> 00:16:42,194\r\n- You got a lulu.\r\n- Yeah. Better not get too close.\r\n\r\n141\r\n00:16:42,320 --> 00:16:44,151\r\n- I never catch colds.\r\n- Really?\r\n\r\n142\r\n00:16:44,280 --> 00:16:46,999\r\nI was reading some sickness\r\nand accident claims figures.\r\n\r\n143\r\n00:16:47,120 --> 00:16:51,557\r\nThe average New Yorker aged between\r\n20 and 50 has two and a half colds a year.\r\n\r\n144\r\n00:16:51,680 --> 00:16:54,035\r\n- That makes me feel just terrible.\r\n- Why?\r\n\r\n145\r\n00:16:54,160 --> 00:16:58,233\r\nIf I have no colds a year, some poor slob\r\nmust have five colds a year.\r\n\r\n146\r\n00:16:58,360 --> 00:17:01,796\r\n- Yeah. It's me.\r\n- You shoulda stayed in bed this morning.\r\n\r\n147\r\n00:17:01,920 --> 00:17:04,275\r\nI shoulda stayed in bed last night.\r\n\r\n148\r\n00:17:05,040 --> 00:17:06,040\r\n19!\r\n\r\n149\r\n00:17:09,640 --> 00:17:11,278\r\nWatch your step.\r\n\r\n150\r\n00:17:11,400 --> 00:17:13,868\r\n- And watch your hands, Mr Kirkeby!\r\n- Pardon?\r\n\r\n151\r\n00:17:14,000 --> 00:17:17,356\r\nOne of these days I'm gonna\r\nshut these doors on you and...\r\n\r\n152\r\n00:17:19,520 --> 00:17:21,120\r\n20 next!\r\n\r\n153\r\n00:17:21,840 --> 00:17:25,469\r\nThat Kubelik. Boy, would I like\r\nto get <i>her</i> on a slow elevator to China!\r\n\r\n154\r\n00:17:25,600 --> 00:17:29,036\r\n- She's the best operator in the building.\r\n- I'm pretty good myself.\r\n\r\n155\r\n00:17:29,160 --> 00:17:32,118\r\n- But she won't give me a date.\r\n- Maybe it's your approach.\r\n\r\n156\r\n00:17:32,240 --> 00:17:35,869\r\nA lot of guys around here have tried\r\nall kinds of approaches. No dice.\r\n\r\n157\r\n00:17:36,000 --> 00:17:39,993\r\n- What's she trying to prove?\r\n- She could just be a nice respectable girl.\r\n\r\n158\r\n00:17:40,120 --> 00:17:42,509\r\nListen to him! Little Lord Fauntleroy.\r\n\r\n159\r\n00:18:06,800 --> 00:18:10,634\r\nHello. Mr Dobisch?\r\nThis is Baxter on the 19th floor.\r\n\r\n160\r\n00:18:10,760 --> 00:18:12,432\r\nOh, Buddy-boy!\r\n\r\n161\r\n00:18:12,560 --> 00:18:17,315\r\nI was just about to call you. I'm sorry\r\nabout that mess on the living room wall.\r\n\r\n162\r\n00:18:17,440 --> 00:18:21,433\r\nMy friend kept insisting Picasso was\r\na bum, so she started to do that mural.\r\n\r\n163\r\n00:18:21,560 --> 00:18:23,915\r\nIt's not Picasso I'm calling about.\r\n\r\n164\r\n00:18:24,040 --> 00:18:28,511\r\nIt's the key to my apartment.\r\nYou're supposed to leave it under the mat.\r\n\r\n165\r\n00:18:28,800 --> 00:18:31,678\r\nBut I did. I distinctly\r\nremember putting it there.\r\n\r\n166\r\n00:18:31,880 --> 00:18:34,758\r\nOh, I found the key all right.\r\nOnly it's the wrong key!\r\n\r\n167\r\n00:18:35,280 --> 00:18:40,877\r\nIt is? No wonder I couldn't get into\r\nthe executive washroom this morning.\r\n\r\n168\r\n00:18:41,000 --> 00:18:43,355\r\nAnd I couldn't get into my apartment!\r\n\r\n169\r\n00:18:43,480 --> 00:18:47,268\r\nSo at 4am I gotta wake up the landlady\r\nand give her a whole song and dance.\r\n\r\n170\r\n00:18:47,400 --> 00:18:50,517\r\nThat's a shame.\r\nI'll send the key right down.\r\n\r\n171\r\n00:18:50,640 --> 00:18:52,517\r\nAnd about your promotion.\r\n\r\n172\r\n00:18:52,640 --> 00:18:55,712\r\nI'll send that efficiency report\r\nto Mr Sheldrake in Personnel.\r\n\r\n173\r\n00:18:55,840 --> 00:18:58,195\r\nYou may hear from him\r\nbefore the day's over.\r\n\r\n174\r\n00:18:58,320 --> 00:19:00,276\r\nThank you, Mr Dobisch.\r\n\r\n175\r\n00:19:26,160 --> 00:19:28,071\r\nFrom Mr Dobisch.\r\n\r\n176\r\n00:19:28,200 --> 00:19:29,200\r\nWait.\r\n\r\n177\r\n00:19:40,400 --> 00:19:42,356\r\nFor Mr Dobisch.\r\n\r\n178\r\n00:19:48,800 --> 00:19:50,756\r\nMm-hm. Mm-hm.\r\n\r\n179\r\n00:20:04,880 --> 00:20:06,632\r\nVanderhof. Public Relations.\r\n\r\n180\r\n00:20:06,760 --> 00:20:08,716\r\nOh, yes, Baxter. Just a minute.\r\n\r\n181\r\n00:20:08,840 --> 00:20:11,991\r\nAll right, Miss Finch.\r\nType up what we got so far.\r\n\r\n182\r\n00:20:14,440 --> 00:20:16,715\r\nLook, I've got you down for tonight...\r\n\r\n183\r\n00:20:16,840 --> 00:20:20,037\r\n...but I'll be using the place myself,\r\nso I'll have to cancel.\r\n\r\n184\r\n00:20:20,160 --> 00:20:22,913\r\nBut it's her birthday.\r\nI already ordered the cake.\r\n\r\n185\r\n00:20:23,040 --> 00:20:27,989\r\nBut I am sick. I got a terrible cold and a\r\nfever. I got to go to bed right after work.\r\n\r\n186\r\n00:20:28,120 --> 00:20:31,715\r\nIf you got a cold, you go to a Turkish bath.\r\nSpend the night. Sweat it out.\r\n\r\n187\r\n00:20:31,840 --> 00:20:35,833\r\nThat's how you get pneumonia. If I got\r\npneumonia, I'd be in bed for a month.\r\n\r\n188\r\n00:20:35,960 --> 00:20:40,192\r\nOK. You made your point. We'll just\r\nhave to do it next Wednesday night.\r\n\r\n189\r\n00:20:40,320 --> 00:20:45,678\r\n- It's the only night I can get away.\r\n- Wednesday, Wednesday... Wednesday.\r\n\r\n190\r\n00:20:47,160 --> 00:20:49,435\r\nI got somebody pencilled in.\r\n\r\n191\r\n00:20:49,560 --> 00:20:52,313\r\nLet me see what I can do.\r\nI'll get back to you.\r\n\r\n192\r\n00:21:02,240 --> 00:21:06,199\r\n- Mr Eichelberger.\r\n- Oh, yes, Baxter. What's your problem?\r\n\r\n193\r\n00:21:07,960 --> 00:21:12,875\r\nWednesday is out? Oh, that throws\r\na little monkey wrench into my agenda.\r\n\r\n194\r\n00:21:13,000 --> 00:21:16,151\r\nThursday? No,\r\nI'm all tied up on Thursday.\r\n\r\n195\r\n00:21:17,480 --> 00:21:20,597\r\nLet's schedule that, uh...\r\nmeeting for Friday.\r\n\r\n196\r\n00:21:20,720 --> 00:21:22,120\r\nFriday.\r\n\r\n197\r\n00:21:23,560 --> 00:21:26,199\r\nLet me see what I can do.\r\nI'll get back to you.\r\n\r\n198\r\n00:21:31,640 --> 00:21:36,350\r\nPremiumwise and billingwise, we are 18\r\nper cent ahead of last year Octoberwise.\r\n\r\n199\r\n00:21:38,960 --> 00:21:41,918\r\nHello? Yeah, Baxter. What's up?\r\n\r\n200\r\n00:21:42,040 --> 00:21:45,157\r\nInstead of Friday, could you\r\npossibly switch to Thursday?\r\n\r\n201\r\n00:21:45,280 --> 00:21:47,953\r\nYou'd be doing me a great favour.\r\n\r\n202\r\n00:21:48,360 --> 00:21:50,715\r\nLet me check. I'll get back to you.\r\n\r\n203\r\n00:21:52,400 --> 00:21:54,834\r\nConsolidated Life. I'll connect you.\r\n\r\n204\r\n00:21:54,960 --> 00:21:56,837\r\nSylvia, it's for you.\r\n\r\n205\r\n00:21:56,960 --> 00:21:57,960\r\nYeah?\r\n\r\n206\r\n00:21:58,800 --> 00:22:00,392\r\nOh, hello.\r\n\r\n207\r\n00:22:00,520 --> 00:22:03,717\r\nSure I got home all right.\r\nYou owe me 45 cents.\r\n\r\n208\r\n00:22:03,840 --> 00:22:07,389\r\nLook, Sylvia. Instead of Friday,\r\ncould we make it Thursday night?\r\n\r\n209\r\n00:22:07,680 --> 00:22:12,549\r\nThursday?! Well, that's\r\n<i>The Untouchables</i> with Bob Stack!\r\n\r\n210\r\n00:22:12,880 --> 00:22:14,480\r\nBob who?\r\n\r\n211\r\n00:22:15,280 --> 00:22:18,829\r\nAll right, so we'll watch it\r\nat the apartment. Big deal!\r\n\r\n212\r\n00:22:22,840 --> 00:22:25,354\r\nHello, Baxter? It's OK for Thursday.\r\n\r\n213\r\n00:22:26,000 --> 00:22:27,956\r\nThank you, Mr Kirkeby.\r\n\r\n214\r\n00:22:37,120 --> 00:22:39,588\r\nMr Eichelberger, it's OK for Friday.\r\n\r\n215\r\n00:22:46,800 --> 00:22:49,553\r\nMr Vanderhof? OK for Wednesday.\r\n\r\n216\r\n00:23:00,040 --> 00:23:01,871\r\nAll right. I'll tell him.\r\n\r\n217\r\n00:23:02,000 --> 00:23:05,675\r\nHey, Baxter, that was Personnel.\r\nMr Sheldrake's secretary.\r\n\r\n218\r\n00:23:05,800 --> 00:23:10,555\r\nShe's been trying to reach you for the last\r\n20 minutes. They want you upstairs.\r\n\r\n219\r\n00:23:11,400 --> 00:23:16,076\r\n- Are you getting promoted? Or fired?\r\n- Would you care to make a small wager?\r\n\r\n220\r\n00:23:16,200 --> 00:23:20,239\r\n- I've been here twice as long as you but...\r\n- Let's say a dollar?\r\n\r\n221\r\n00:23:20,360 --> 00:23:21,873\r\nIt's a bet!\r\n\r\n222\r\n00:23:34,560 --> 00:23:36,710\r\n- Going up?\r\n- Oh! Excuse me.\r\n\r\n223\r\n00:23:36,840 --> 00:23:42,676\r\n27, please. Drive carefully. You're carrying\r\nprecious cargo. I mean manpowerwise.\r\n\r\n224\r\n00:23:43,080 --> 00:23:44,080\r\n27.\r\n\r\n225\r\n00:23:44,360 --> 00:23:48,148\r\nYou may not realise it, but I am\r\nin the top ten, efficiencywise...\r\n\r\n226\r\n00:23:48,280 --> 00:23:50,953\r\n...and this may be the day promotionwise.\r\n\r\n227\r\n00:23:51,080 --> 00:23:53,640\r\nYou're beginning to sound\r\nlike Mr Kirkeby already.\r\n\r\n228\r\n00:23:53,760 --> 00:23:57,639\r\n- Why not, as they're kicking me upstairs?\r\n- Couldn't happen to a nicer guy.\r\n\r\n229\r\n00:23:57,760 --> 00:24:01,309\r\nYou know, you're the only one\r\nwho takes his hat off in the elevator.\r\n\r\n230\r\n00:24:01,440 --> 00:24:03,635\r\nSomething happens to men in elevators.\r\n\r\n231\r\n00:24:03,760 --> 00:24:06,638\r\nIt's the change of altitude.\r\nThe blood rushes to their head.\r\n\r\n232\r\n00:24:06,760 --> 00:24:09,832\r\n- I could tell you stories...\r\n- I'd love to hear 'em.\r\n\r\n233\r\n00:24:09,960 --> 00:24:12,428\r\nWe could have lunch\r\nin the cafeteria sometime.\r\n\r\n234\r\n00:24:12,560 --> 00:24:14,437\r\nOr some evening, after work?\r\n\r\n235\r\n00:24:14,560 --> 00:24:16,630\r\n- 27.\r\n- Oh.\r\n\r\n236\r\n00:24:16,760 --> 00:24:19,320\r\n- I hope everything goes all right.\r\n- I hope so.\r\n\r\n237\r\n00:24:19,440 --> 00:24:22,079\r\nThey <i>would</i> call me today,\r\nwhat with my cold.\r\n\r\n238\r\n00:24:22,200 --> 00:24:24,555\r\n- How do I look?\r\n- Fine. Wait.\r\n\r\n239\r\n00:24:25,400 --> 00:24:26,913\r\nThank you.\r\n\r\n240\r\n00:24:27,040 --> 00:24:31,670\r\nI noticed, when you were still on the\r\nlocal elevator, you always wore a flower.\r\n\r\n241\r\n00:24:31,800 --> 00:24:34,189\r\nGood luck. And wipe your nose.\r\n\r\n242\r\n00:24:49,280 --> 00:24:52,590\r\nCC Baxter, Ordinary Premium Accounting.\r\nMr Sheldrake called me.\r\n\r\n243\r\n00:24:52,720 --> 00:24:55,393\r\nI called you. That is,\r\nI tried to for 20 minutes.\r\n\r\n244\r\n00:24:55,520 --> 00:24:57,476\r\n- I'm sorry.\r\n- Go on in.\r\n\r\n245\r\n00:25:08,720 --> 00:25:10,233\r\n- Baxter?\r\n- Yes, sir.\r\n\r\n246\r\n00:25:10,360 --> 00:25:12,316\r\nCome in, come in.\r\n\r\n247\r\n00:25:13,240 --> 00:25:16,073\r\nI was sort of wondering\r\nwhat you looked like, Baxter.\r\n\r\n248\r\n00:25:16,200 --> 00:25:18,589\r\n- Sit down.\r\n- Yes, Mr Sheldrake.\r\n\r\n249\r\n00:25:20,040 --> 00:25:22,679\r\nBeen hearing some nice things about you.\r\n\r\n250\r\n00:25:22,800 --> 00:25:25,758\r\nMr Dobisch says you're loyal,\r\ncooperative, resourceful.\r\n\r\n251\r\n00:25:25,880 --> 00:25:30,078\r\n- Mr Dobisch said that?\r\n- Mr Kirkeby tells me you often work late...\r\n\r\n252\r\n00:25:30,200 --> 00:25:33,351\r\n...without overtime.\r\n- You know how it is. Things pile up.\r\n\r\n253\r\n00:25:34,040 --> 00:25:37,510\r\nMr Vanderhof in Public Relations and\r\nMr Eichelberger in Mortgage and Loans...\r\n\r\n254\r\n00:25:37,640 --> 00:25:40,438\r\n...would both like you\r\ntransferred to their departments.\r\n\r\n255\r\n00:25:40,560 --> 00:25:42,391\r\nVery flattering.\r\n\r\n256\r\n00:25:43,440 --> 00:25:47,513\r\nTell me, Baxter. Just what is it\r\nthat makes you so popular?\r\n\r\n257\r\n00:25:47,640 --> 00:25:50,916\r\n- I don't know.\r\n- Think.\r\n\r\n258\r\n00:25:55,960 --> 00:25:59,839\r\n- Would you mind repeating the question?\r\n- Look, Baxter. I'm not stupid.\r\n\r\n259\r\n00:25:59,960 --> 00:26:04,351\r\nI know everything that goes on\r\nin this building every day of the year.\r\n\r\n260\r\n00:26:04,480 --> 00:26:05,879\r\nYou do?\r\n\r\n261\r\n00:26:06,000 --> 00:26:10,357\r\nIn 1957 we had an employee here,\r\nname of Fowler. He was very popular too.\r\n\r\n262\r\n00:26:10,480 --> 00:26:13,074\r\nIt turned out\r\nhe was running a bookie joint...\r\n\r\n263\r\n00:26:13,200 --> 00:26:16,590\r\n...tying up our switchboard, using\r\nour IBM machines to figure the odds.\r\n\r\n264\r\n00:26:16,720 --> 00:26:20,838\r\nThe day before the Kentucky Derby I\r\ncalled in the vice squad, who raided him.\r\n\r\n265\r\n00:26:20,960 --> 00:26:22,916\r\n- The vice squad?\r\n- That's right.\r\n\r\n266\r\n00:26:23,040 --> 00:26:26,191\r\nWhat's that got to do with me?\r\nI'm not running any bookie joint.\r\n\r\n267\r\n00:26:26,320 --> 00:26:29,676\r\n- Just what kind of joint are you running?\r\n- Sir?\r\n\r\n268\r\n00:26:29,800 --> 00:26:34,669\r\nA key is floating around from Kirkeby\r\nto Vanderhof to Eichelberger to Dobisch.\r\n\r\n269\r\n00:26:34,800 --> 00:26:36,711\r\nIt's the key to a certain apartment.\r\n\r\n270\r\n00:26:36,840 --> 00:26:40,116\r\n- Know who that apartment belongs to?\r\n- Who?\r\n\r\n271\r\n00:26:40,560 --> 00:26:43,472\r\nLoyal, resourceful, cooperative CC Baxter.\r\n\r\n272\r\n00:26:45,920 --> 00:26:48,275\r\n- Oh.\r\n- Are you going to deny it?\r\n\r\n273\r\n00:26:49,360 --> 00:26:53,035\r\nNo. I'm not going to deny it.\r\nIf you'd just let me explain.\r\n\r\n274\r\n00:26:53,680 --> 00:26:55,432\r\nYou'd better.\r\n\r\n275\r\n00:26:55,560 --> 00:26:56,960\r\nWell...\r\n\r\n276\r\n00:26:58,160 --> 00:27:02,756\r\n...about a year ago, I was going to night\r\nschool, studying advanced accounting.\r\n\r\n277\r\n00:27:02,880 --> 00:27:07,670\r\nOne of the guys in our department - lives\r\nin Jersey - had to go to a banquet in town.\r\n\r\n278\r\n00:27:07,800 --> 00:27:12,032\r\nHe needed someplace to change\r\ninto a tuxedo, so I gave him the key.\r\n\r\n279\r\n00:27:12,160 --> 00:27:17,871\r\nWord must've gotten out because all sorts\r\nof guys were suddenly going to banquets.\r\n\r\n280\r\n00:27:18,000 --> 00:27:22,676\r\nYou give the key to one guy, you can't\r\nsay no to another. It all got out of hand.\r\n\r\n281\r\n00:27:25,560 --> 00:27:28,836\r\nBaxter, an insurance company\r\nis founded on public trust.\r\n\r\n282\r\n00:27:28,960 --> 00:27:32,111\r\nAny employee who conducts himself\r\nin a manner unbecoming...\r\n\r\n283\r\n00:27:32,240 --> 00:27:35,152\r\nHow many charter members\r\nare there in this little club?\r\n\r\n284\r\n00:27:35,280 --> 00:27:38,909\r\nJust those four. Out of a total of 31,259.\r\n\r\n285\r\n00:27:39,040 --> 00:27:42,953\r\nSo actually we can be very proud\r\nof our personnel... percentagewise.\r\n\r\n286\r\n00:27:43,080 --> 00:27:47,551\r\nThat's not the point. Four rotten apples\r\nin a barrel, however large the barrel...\r\n\r\n287\r\n00:27:47,680 --> 00:27:50,752\r\n- Do you realise if this ever leaked out...\r\n- It won't!\r\n\r\n288\r\n00:27:50,880 --> 00:27:55,670\r\nBelieve me. Never again. Nobody\r\nis gonna use my apartment from now on.\r\n\r\n289\r\n00:27:55,800 --> 00:27:58,360\r\n- Where is your apartment?\r\n- West 67th Street.\r\n\r\n290\r\n00:27:58,480 --> 00:28:03,759\r\nYou have no idea what I go through with\r\nthe neighbours, the landlady and the key.\r\n\r\n291\r\n00:28:03,880 --> 00:28:05,836\r\nHow do you work it with the key?\r\n\r\n292\r\n00:28:05,960 --> 00:28:10,636\r\nI slip it to 'em in the office and they leave\r\nit under a mat. Never again. I promise.\r\n\r\n293\r\n00:28:14,200 --> 00:28:17,954\r\n- Yes, Miss Olsen?\r\n- Mrs Sheldrake, returning your call. On 2.\r\n\r\n294\r\n00:28:22,280 --> 00:28:24,316\r\n<i> Yes, dear. Where were you?</i>\r\n\r\n295\r\n00:28:25,080 --> 00:28:29,676\r\nYou had to take Tommy to the dentist?\r\nNo cavities? Good. Hold it, dear.\r\n\r\n296\r\n00:28:29,800 --> 00:28:32,712\r\n- Where are you going, Baxter?\r\n- I don't wanna intrude.\r\n\r\n297\r\n00:28:32,840 --> 00:28:36,037\r\n- Since this is straightened out...\r\n- I'm not through with you yet.\r\n\r\n298\r\n00:28:36,160 --> 00:28:38,276\r\nI won't be home for dinner tonight.\r\n\r\n299\r\n00:28:38,400 --> 00:28:42,234\r\nThe branch manager from Kansas City\r\nis in town. I'm taking him to the theatre.\r\n\r\n300\r\n00:28:42,360 --> 00:28:44,112\r\n<i>Music Man.</i> What else?\r\n\r\n301\r\n00:28:44,240 --> 00:28:46,674\r\nNo, don't wait up for me,\r\ndarling. Goodbye.\r\n\r\n302\r\n00:28:47,840 --> 00:28:51,116\r\nTell me, Baxter.\r\nHave you seen <i>Music Man?</i>\r\n\r\n303\r\n00:28:51,240 --> 00:28:53,754\r\nNot yet. I hear it's one swell show.\r\n\r\n304\r\n00:28:53,880 --> 00:28:56,030\r\nHow would you like to go tonight?\r\n\r\n305\r\n00:28:56,160 --> 00:29:00,278\r\nYou and me? I thought you were taking\r\nthe branch manager from Kansas City.\r\n\r\n306\r\n00:29:00,400 --> 00:29:03,551\r\nNo, I have other plans.\r\nYou can have both tickets.\r\n\r\n307\r\n00:29:03,680 --> 00:29:05,636\r\nWell... that's very kind of you.\r\n\r\n308\r\n00:29:05,760 --> 00:29:09,639\r\nBut I'm not feeling well. I've got\r\nthis cold. I'm gonna go right home.\r\n\r\n309\r\n00:29:09,760 --> 00:29:13,196\r\nBaxter, you're not reading me.\r\nI told you I have plans.\r\n\r\n310\r\n00:29:13,600 --> 00:29:16,672\r\nSo do I. I'm gonna take\r\nfour aspirins, get into bed.\r\n\r\n311\r\n00:29:16,800 --> 00:29:18,950\r\nSo give the tickets to somebody else.\r\n\r\n312\r\n00:29:19,360 --> 00:29:23,831\r\nLook, Baxter. I'm not just giving\r\nthese tickets. I wanna swap them.\r\n\r\n313\r\n00:29:23,960 --> 00:29:26,030\r\nSwap 'em? For what?\r\n\r\n314\r\n00:29:28,240 --> 00:29:32,870\r\nIt also says here that you are\r\nalert, astute and quite imaginative.\r\n\r\n315\r\n00:29:34,080 --> 00:29:35,080\r\nOh?\r\n\r\n316\r\n00:29:40,760 --> 00:29:41,760\r\nOh...\r\n\r\n317\r\n00:29:51,760 --> 00:29:55,719\r\nThat's good thinking, Baxter. There's\r\ngonna be a shift in personnel next month.\r\n\r\n318\r\n00:29:55,840 --> 00:29:59,549\r\nAnd as far as I'm concerned,\r\nyou are executive material.\r\n\r\n319\r\n00:29:59,680 --> 00:30:02,035\r\n- I am?\r\n- Now put down the key.\r\n\r\n320\r\n00:30:05,080 --> 00:30:07,036\r\nAnd put down the address.\r\n\r\n321\r\n00:30:08,960 --> 00:30:13,909\r\nIt's on the second floor. There's no name\r\nover the door. It just says apartment 2A.\r\n\r\n322\r\n00:30:14,760 --> 00:30:16,751\r\n- It's that cold.\r\n- Relax, Baxter.\r\n\r\n323\r\n00:30:16,880 --> 00:30:18,836\r\nYes, thank you, sir.\r\n\r\n324\r\n00:30:20,800 --> 00:30:23,758\r\nYou will be careful with\r\nthe record player? Shh.\r\n\r\n325\r\n00:30:23,880 --> 00:30:25,836\r\nOh, and about the liquor.\r\n\r\n326\r\n00:30:25,960 --> 00:30:30,351\r\nI ordered some this morning.\r\nI don't know when they'll deliver it.\r\n\r\n327\r\n00:30:31,360 --> 00:30:34,272\r\n- This is going to be our little secret.\r\n- Of course.\r\n\r\n328\r\n00:30:34,400 --> 00:30:36,960\r\n- You know how people talk.\r\n- Don't worry about that.\r\n\r\n329\r\n00:30:37,080 --> 00:30:40,675\r\n- Not that I have anything to hide.\r\n- No! Anyway, it's none of my business.\r\n\r\n330\r\n00:30:40,800 --> 00:30:44,509\r\nFour apples, five apples.\r\nWhat's the difference?\r\n\r\n331\r\n00:30:44,640 --> 00:30:46,596\r\nPercentagewise.\r\n\r\n332\r\n00:30:46,720 --> 00:30:49,188\r\nHere you are, Baxter. Have a nice time.\r\n\r\n333\r\n00:30:49,320 --> 00:30:51,276\r\nYou too, sir.\r\n\r\n334\r\n00:31:22,000 --> 00:31:25,788\r\nSo I figure, a man in his position,\r\nhe'll take me to El Morocco, maybe 21.\r\n\r\n335\r\n00:31:25,920 --> 00:31:30,277\r\nInstead he takes me to Hamburger\r\nHeaven and some schnook's apartment.\r\n\r\n336\r\n00:31:35,040 --> 00:31:36,996\r\n- Good night.\r\n- Good night.\r\n\r\n337\r\n00:31:38,920 --> 00:31:41,195\r\nOh! Miss Kubelik?\r\n\r\n338\r\n00:31:41,320 --> 00:31:44,357\r\nI've been waiting for you.\r\nI almost didn't recognise you.\r\n\r\n339\r\n00:31:44,480 --> 00:31:47,517\r\nThis is the first time\r\nI've seen you in civilian clothes.\r\n\r\n340\r\n00:31:47,640 --> 00:31:49,835\r\n- How'd it go on the 27th floor?\r\n- Great.\r\n\r\n341\r\n00:31:49,960 --> 00:31:52,269\r\n- Look, have you seen <i>The Music Man?</i>\r\n- No.\r\n\r\n342\r\n00:31:52,400 --> 00:31:53,958\r\n- Would you like to?\r\n- Sure.\r\n\r\n343\r\n00:31:54,080 --> 00:31:56,310\r\nWe could get a bite to eat first,\r\nand then go.\r\n\r\n344\r\n00:31:56,440 --> 00:31:57,953\r\n- Oh, you mean tonight?\r\n- Yeah.\r\n\r\n345\r\n00:31:58,080 --> 00:32:01,038\r\n- I'm sorry, I can't. I'm meeting somebody.\r\n- Oh.\r\n\r\n346\r\n00:32:01,160 --> 00:32:04,596\r\n- You mean... like a girlfriend?\r\n- No. Like a man.\r\n\r\n347\r\n00:32:04,720 --> 00:32:09,111\r\nI wasn't trying to be personal. The fellas\r\nin the office were wondering if you ever...\r\n\r\n348\r\n00:32:09,240 --> 00:32:11,117\r\nYou tell 'em now and then.\r\n\r\n349\r\n00:32:11,240 --> 00:32:15,392\r\nThis date, is it... just a date?\r\nOr is it something serious?\r\n\r\n350\r\n00:32:15,520 --> 00:32:18,830\r\nWell, it used to be serious.\r\nAt least, I was. But he wasn't.\r\n\r\n351\r\n00:32:18,960 --> 00:32:21,235\r\nSo now the whole thing's\r\nmore or less kaput.\r\n\r\n352\r\n00:32:21,360 --> 00:32:23,874\r\n- In that case, couldn't you...\r\n- I'm afraid not.\r\n\r\n353\r\n00:32:24,000 --> 00:32:27,959\r\nI promised I'd have a drink with him.\r\nHe's been calling me all week.\r\n\r\n354\r\n00:32:28,600 --> 00:32:30,750\r\nI understand.\r\n\r\n355\r\n00:32:30,880 --> 00:32:35,237\r\nWell, it was just an idea. I hate\r\nto see a theatre ticket go to waste.\r\n\r\n356\r\n00:32:35,360 --> 00:32:38,318\r\n- What time does the show go on?\r\n- 8.30.\r\n\r\n357\r\n00:32:38,440 --> 00:32:40,715\r\nWell, I could meet you at the theatre.\r\n\r\n358\r\n00:32:40,840 --> 00:32:44,753\r\nThat's wonderful!\r\nIt's the Majestic on 44th Street.\r\n\r\n359\r\n00:32:44,880 --> 00:32:46,677\r\nI'll meet you in the lobby.\r\n\r\n360\r\n00:32:46,800 --> 00:32:50,156\r\nYou know, I felt so lousy\r\nthis morning. Had 101 fever.\r\n\r\n361\r\n00:32:50,280 --> 00:32:53,636\r\nNow along comes my promotion\r\nand us - 11th row centre.\r\n\r\n362\r\n00:32:53,760 --> 00:32:55,637\r\nAnd you said I should've stayed in bed.\r\n\r\n363\r\n00:32:55,760 --> 00:32:57,830\r\n- How is your cold?\r\n- What cold?\r\n\r\n364\r\n00:32:57,960 --> 00:33:01,839\r\nAfter the show we could go out\r\non the town.\r\n\r\n365\r\n00:33:01,960 --> 00:33:04,633\r\n- I've been taking from Arthur Murray.\r\n- So I see.\r\n\r\n366\r\n00:33:04,760 --> 00:33:07,638\r\nThere's a great band\r\nat El Chico, in the Village.\r\n\r\n367\r\n00:33:07,760 --> 00:33:11,150\r\n- Around the corner from where you live.\r\n- Sounds good.\r\n\r\n368\r\n00:33:11,280 --> 00:33:15,717\r\n- How do you know where I live?\r\n- Oh, I... even know who you live with.\r\n\r\n369\r\n00:33:15,840 --> 00:33:17,796\r\nYour sister and brother-in-law.\r\n\r\n370\r\n00:33:17,920 --> 00:33:21,708\r\nI know when you were born and where.\r\nI know all sorts of things about you.\r\n\r\n371\r\n00:33:21,840 --> 00:33:23,193\r\nHow come?\r\n\r\n372\r\n00:33:23,320 --> 00:33:27,836\r\nA couple of months ago I looked up\r\nyour card in the group insurance file.\r\n\r\n373\r\n00:33:27,960 --> 00:33:31,714\r\nI know your height and your weight\r\nand your social security number.\r\n\r\n374\r\n00:33:31,840 --> 00:33:35,594\r\nYou had mumps and measles\r\nand you had your appendix out.\r\n\r\n375\r\n00:33:36,520 --> 00:33:39,557\r\nDon't mention the appendix\r\nto the fellas in the office.\r\n\r\n376\r\n00:33:39,680 --> 00:33:44,231\r\nI wouldn't want 'em to get the wrong idea\r\nabout how you found out. Bye.\r\n\r\n377\r\n00:33:47,440 --> 00:33:48,440\r\n8.30!\r\n\r\n378\r\n00:34:36,320 --> 00:34:40,233\r\n- Good evening, Mr Sheldrake.\r\n- Please, Fran. Not so loud.\r\n\r\n379\r\n00:34:40,360 --> 00:34:42,715\r\nStill afraid someone\r\nmight see us together?\r\n\r\n380\r\n00:34:42,840 --> 00:34:46,310\r\n- Let me take your coat.\r\n- No, Jeff. I can't stay very long.\r\n\r\n381\r\n00:34:47,600 --> 00:34:50,672\r\n- Can I have a frozen daiquiri?\r\n- It's on the way.\r\n\r\n382\r\n00:34:51,720 --> 00:34:55,030\r\n- I see you went ahead and cut your hair.\r\n- That's right.\r\n\r\n383\r\n00:34:55,160 --> 00:34:58,357\r\n- You know I liked it better long.\r\n- I know.\r\n\r\n384\r\n00:34:58,480 --> 00:35:01,233\r\nYou want a lock to carry in your wallet?\r\n\r\n385\r\n00:35:01,960 --> 00:35:05,350\r\n- Evening, lady. Nice to see you again.\r\n- Thank you.\r\n\r\n386\r\n00:35:06,440 --> 00:35:08,635\r\nHow long has it been, Fran? A month?\r\n\r\n387\r\n00:35:08,760 --> 00:35:11,320\r\nSix weeks. But who's counting?\r\n\r\n388\r\n00:35:12,360 --> 00:35:14,316\r\nI missed you.\r\n\r\n389\r\n00:35:16,760 --> 00:35:18,716\r\nLike old times.\r\n\r\n390\r\n00:35:18,840 --> 00:35:21,434\r\nSame booth. Same song.\r\n\r\n391\r\n00:35:22,280 --> 00:35:26,239\r\n- It's been hell.\r\n- Same sauce. Sweet-and-sour.\r\n\r\n392\r\n00:35:28,680 --> 00:35:31,752\r\nYou don't know what it's like,\r\nnext to you in that elevator.\r\n\r\n393\r\n00:35:31,880 --> 00:35:34,952\r\n\"Good morning, Miss Kubelik.\"\r\n\"Good night, Mr Sheldrake.\"\r\n\r\n394\r\n00:35:35,080 --> 00:35:37,514\r\nI'm still crazy about you, Fran.\r\n\r\n395\r\n00:35:37,640 --> 00:35:42,919\r\nLet's not start on that again, Jeff. Please?\r\nI'm just beginning to get over it.\r\n\r\n396\r\n00:35:44,200 --> 00:35:46,555\r\nI don't believe you.\r\n\r\n397\r\n00:35:47,720 --> 00:35:50,598\r\nLook, Jeff. We had two\r\nwonderful months this summer.\r\n\r\n398\r\n00:35:50,720 --> 00:35:53,473\r\nBut that was it. Happens all the time.\r\n\r\n399\r\n00:35:53,600 --> 00:35:57,559\r\nWife and kids go away to the country and\r\nthe boss has a fling with his secretary...\r\n\r\n400\r\n00:35:57,680 --> 00:36:00,319\r\n...or the manicurist, or the elevator girl.\r\n\r\n401\r\n00:36:00,440 --> 00:36:03,716\r\nCome September,\r\nthe picnic's over. Goodbye.\r\n\r\n402\r\n00:36:03,840 --> 00:36:07,719\r\nThe kids go back to school,\r\nthe boss goes back to the wife...\r\n\r\n403\r\n00:36:07,840 --> 00:36:09,796\r\n...and the girl...\r\n\r\n404\r\n00:36:11,080 --> 00:36:13,958\r\nThey don't make these shrimp\r\nlike they used to.\r\n\r\n405\r\n00:36:17,000 --> 00:36:19,560\r\nI never said goodbye, Fran.\r\n\r\n406\r\n00:36:21,040 --> 00:36:26,194\r\nFor a while there, you try kidding yourself\r\nthat you're going with an unmarried man.\r\n\r\n407\r\n00:36:26,320 --> 00:36:28,993\r\nThen one day he keeps\r\nlooking at his watch...\r\n\r\n408\r\n00:36:29,120 --> 00:36:31,634\r\n...and asks you if any lipstick's showing...\r\n\r\n409\r\n00:36:31,760 --> 00:36:35,116\r\n...then rushes out to catch\r\nthe 7.14 to White Plains.\r\n\r\n410\r\n00:36:36,280 --> 00:36:39,716\r\nSo you fix yourself\r\na cup of instant coffee...\r\n\r\n411\r\n00:36:39,840 --> 00:36:43,435\r\n...and you sit there\r\nby yourself and you think...\r\n\r\n412\r\n00:36:44,400 --> 00:36:47,551\r\n...and it all begins to look so... ugly.\r\n\r\n413\r\n00:36:50,920 --> 00:36:54,595\r\nHow do you think I felt\r\nriding home on that 7.14 train?\r\n\r\n414\r\n00:36:54,720 --> 00:36:58,759\r\nWhy do you keep calling me, Jeff?\r\nWhat do you want from me?\r\n\r\n415\r\n00:36:58,880 --> 00:37:00,836\r\nI want you back, Fran.\r\n\r\n416\r\n00:37:00,960 --> 00:37:04,714\r\nSorry, Mr Sheldrake. I'm full up.\r\nYou'll have to take the next elevator.\r\n\r\n417\r\n00:37:04,840 --> 00:37:08,594\r\nYou're not giving me a chance, Fran.\r\nI have something to tell you.\r\n\r\n418\r\n00:37:08,720 --> 00:37:12,429\r\n- Go ahead. Tell me.\r\n- Not here. Can't we go someplace else?\r\n\r\n419\r\n00:37:12,560 --> 00:37:15,279\r\n- No. I have a date at 8.30.\r\n- Oh?\r\n\r\n420\r\n00:37:15,640 --> 00:37:19,315\r\n- Important?\r\n- Not very, but I'm gonna be there anyway.\r\n\r\n421\r\n00:37:19,440 --> 00:37:22,000\r\n- You ready order dinner now?\r\n- No. No dinner.\r\n\r\n422\r\n00:37:22,120 --> 00:37:24,509\r\nJust bring us two more drinks, will you?\r\n\r\n423\r\n00:37:43,640 --> 00:37:46,393\r\nFran, do you remember\r\nthat last weekend we had?\r\n\r\n424\r\n00:37:46,520 --> 00:37:51,196\r\nDo I! That leaky boat you rented, and me\r\nin a black negligee and a life preserver.\r\n\r\n425\r\n00:37:51,320 --> 00:37:53,595\r\nDo you remember what we talked about?\r\n\r\n426\r\n00:37:53,720 --> 00:37:57,190\r\n- We talked about a lot of things.\r\n- I mean about my getting a divorce.\r\n\r\n427\r\n00:37:57,320 --> 00:37:59,595\r\n<i>We</i> didn't talk about it, Jeff. You did.\r\n\r\n428\r\n00:37:59,720 --> 00:38:01,676\r\nYou didn't believe me, did you?\r\n\r\n429\r\n00:38:01,800 --> 00:38:06,078\r\nThey got it on a long-playing record now.\r\n\"Music to String Her Along By.\"\r\n\r\n430\r\n00:38:06,200 --> 00:38:10,830\r\n\"My wife doesn't understand me. You're\r\nthe best thing that ever happened to me.\"\r\n\r\n431\r\n00:38:10,960 --> 00:38:14,157\r\n- That's enough, Fran.\r\n- \"Trust me, baby. We'll work it out.\"\r\n\r\n432\r\n00:38:14,280 --> 00:38:16,874\r\n- You're not being funny.\r\n- I wasn't trying.\r\n\r\n433\r\n00:38:17,400 --> 00:38:21,234\r\n- Fran, just listen to me for a minute.\r\n- All right. I'm sorry.\r\n\r\n434\r\n00:38:21,360 --> 00:38:26,229\r\nI saw my lawyer this morning. I wanted\r\nhis advice about the best way to handle it.\r\n\r\n435\r\n00:38:26,360 --> 00:38:28,715\r\n- Handle what?\r\n- What do you think?\r\n\r\n436\r\n00:38:30,120 --> 00:38:34,432\r\nLet's get something straight, Jeff.\r\nI never asked you to leave your wife.\r\n\r\n437\r\n00:38:34,560 --> 00:38:37,199\r\nOf course not. You had\r\nnothing to do with it.\r\n\r\n438\r\n00:38:39,120 --> 00:38:41,156\r\nAre you sure that's what you want?\r\n\r\n439\r\n00:38:42,160 --> 00:38:45,630\r\nI'm sure... if you'll just tell me\r\nthat you still love me.\r\n\r\n440\r\n00:38:48,720 --> 00:38:50,676\r\nYou know I do.\r\n\r\n441\r\n00:38:53,720 --> 00:38:54,720\r\nFran.\r\n\r\n442\r\n00:38:58,800 --> 00:39:00,756\r\nJeff, darling...\r\n\r\n443\r\n00:39:06,920 --> 00:39:09,878\r\nIt is getting crowded. Let's get out of here.\r\n\r\n444\r\n00:39:40,960 --> 00:39:41,960\r\nTaxi!\r\n\r\n445\r\n00:39:42,560 --> 00:39:45,996\r\n- Jeff, I have that date, remember?\r\n- But I love you, remember?\r\n\r\n446\r\n00:39:46,120 --> 00:39:48,634\r\nWhere are we going?\r\n\r\n447\r\n00:39:48,760 --> 00:39:51,433\r\n- Not back to that leaky boat?\r\n- I promise.\r\n\r\n448\r\n00:39:55,800 --> 00:39:58,155\r\n51 West 67th.\r\n\r\n449\r\n00:40:39,440 --> 00:40:41,396\r\nCongratulations.\r\n\r\n450\r\n00:40:56,160 --> 00:40:59,038\r\nWould you mind? CC Baxter - that's me.\r\n\r\n451\r\n00:41:02,400 --> 00:41:04,356\r\nThank you.\r\n\r\n452\r\n00:41:19,000 --> 00:41:22,356\r\nHi, Buddy-boy.\r\nCongratulations and all that jazz.\r\n\r\n453\r\n00:41:22,480 --> 00:41:25,836\r\n- Hi, fellas.\r\n- Well, you made it, just like we promised.\r\n\r\n454\r\n00:41:25,960 --> 00:41:29,032\r\nQuite an office.\r\nName on the door, rug on the floor.\r\n\r\n455\r\n00:41:29,160 --> 00:41:33,676\r\nTeamwork: That's what counts in this\r\norganisation. All for one and one for all.\r\n\r\n456\r\n00:41:33,800 --> 00:41:35,756\r\n- Know what I mean?\r\n- I have a vague idea.\r\n\r\n457\r\n00:41:35,880 --> 00:41:38,917\r\nBaxter, we're a little disappointed\r\nin you, gratitudewise.\r\n\r\n458\r\n00:41:39,040 --> 00:41:42,350\r\n- Oh, I'm very grateful.\r\n- Then why are you locking us out?\r\n\r\n459\r\n00:41:42,480 --> 00:41:47,873\r\nWell, it's been sort of rough the past few\r\nweeks, what with my cold and... like that.\r\n\r\n460\r\n00:41:48,000 --> 00:41:50,719\r\nWe went to bat for you.\r\nNow you won't play ball with us.\r\n\r\n461\r\n00:41:50,840 --> 00:41:54,992\r\nAfter all, it's my apartment. It's\r\nprivate property, not a public playground.\r\n\r\n462\r\n00:41:55,120 --> 00:41:59,193\r\nSo you got yourself a girl. That's OK\r\nwith us. But not every night in the week!\r\n\r\n463\r\n00:41:59,320 --> 00:42:00,992\r\nHow selfish can you get?\r\n\r\n464\r\n00:42:01,120 --> 00:42:04,749\r\nLast week I had to use my nephew's car\r\nand take Sylvia to a drive-in in Jersey.\r\n\r\n465\r\n00:42:04,880 --> 00:42:07,792\r\nI'm too old for that sort of thing -\r\nI mean in a Volkswagen.\r\n\r\n466\r\n00:42:07,920 --> 00:42:11,037\r\nI sympathise with you.\r\nBelieve me, I'm very sorry.\r\n\r\n467\r\n00:42:11,160 --> 00:42:14,357\r\n- You'll be a lot sorrier.\r\n- Are you threatening me?\r\n\r\n468\r\n00:42:14,480 --> 00:42:17,438\r\nListen, Baxter. We made you\r\nand we can break you.\r\n\r\n469\r\n00:42:18,640 --> 00:42:21,438\r\n- Good morning, Mr Sheldrake.\r\n- Good morning, gentlemen.\r\n\r\n470\r\n00:42:21,560 --> 00:42:25,519\r\n- Baxter, do you like your office?\r\n- Yes, sir. I wanna thank you very much.\r\n\r\n471\r\n00:42:25,640 --> 00:42:28,438\r\nDon't thank me.\r\nYour friends here recommended you.\r\n\r\n472\r\n00:42:28,560 --> 00:42:32,189\r\n- We just dropped by to wish him luck.\r\n- We know you won't let us down.\r\n\r\n473\r\n00:42:32,320 --> 00:42:36,871\r\nSo long, fellas. Drop in any time.\r\nThe door is always open... to my office.\r\n\r\n474\r\n00:42:37,720 --> 00:42:39,711\r\nI like the way you handled that, Baxter.\r\n\r\n475\r\n00:42:39,840 --> 00:42:42,308\r\n- How does it feel to be an executive?\r\n- Oh, fine.\r\n\r\n476\r\n00:42:42,440 --> 00:42:46,115\r\n- I'll work hard to justify your confidence.\r\n- I'm sure you will.\r\n\r\n477\r\n00:42:46,240 --> 00:42:50,836\r\nAbout the apartment. Now that you've got\r\na raise, can't we afford a second key?\r\n\r\n478\r\n00:42:50,960 --> 00:42:53,269\r\n- I guess so.\r\n- You know my secretary, Miss Olsen?\r\n\r\n479\r\n00:42:53,400 --> 00:42:56,073\r\n- Oh, yeah. Is she the lucky girl that?\r\n- Oh, no, no.\r\n\r\n480\r\n00:42:56,200 --> 00:43:01,274\r\nI just meant that she's kind of a busybody,\r\nand passing that key back and forth...\r\n\r\n481\r\n00:43:01,400 --> 00:43:03,914\r\n- Why take chances?\r\n- You can't be too careful.\r\n\r\n482\r\n00:43:04,040 --> 00:43:06,952\r\nOh, I... have something\r\nI think belongs to you.\r\n\r\n483\r\n00:43:07,080 --> 00:43:09,514\r\n- Me?\r\n- I mean the young lady, whoever she is.\r\n\r\n484\r\n00:43:09,640 --> 00:43:12,279\r\n- I found it when I got back last night.\r\n- Oh. Thanks.\r\n\r\n485\r\n00:43:12,400 --> 00:43:15,756\r\nThe mirror is broken.\r\nIt was broken when I found it.\r\n\r\n486\r\n00:43:17,400 --> 00:43:20,119\r\n- Yeah. She threw it at me.\r\n- Sir?\r\n\r\n487\r\n00:43:20,240 --> 00:43:22,629\r\nYou know how it is.\r\nThey always give you a bad time.\r\n\r\n488\r\n00:43:22,760 --> 00:43:23,795\r\nYeah, I know how it is.\r\n\r\n489\r\n00:43:23,920 --> 00:43:28,471\r\nYou see a girl every week for laughs and\r\nthey think you're gonna divorce your wife.\r\n\r\n490\r\n00:43:28,600 --> 00:43:31,672\r\n- Now I ask you, is that fair?\r\n- No, sir. It's very unfair.\r\n\r\n491\r\n00:43:31,800 --> 00:43:33,711\r\n- Especially to your wife.\r\n- Yeah.\r\n\r\n492\r\n00:43:34,120 --> 00:43:38,511\r\nYou know, Baxter, I envy you. A bachelor,\r\nall the dames you want, no complications.\r\n\r\n493\r\n00:43:38,640 --> 00:43:40,153\r\nThat's the life all right.\r\n\r\n494\r\n00:43:40,280 --> 00:43:42,475\r\n- Put me down for Thursday again.\r\n- Roger.\r\n\r\n495\r\n00:43:42,600 --> 00:43:44,750\r\nAnd I'll get that other key.\r\n\r\n496\r\n00:43:56,480 --> 00:44:00,189\r\n- Merry Christmas. I'll connect you.\r\n- Merry Christmas. Consolidated Life.\r\n\r\n497\r\n00:44:00,320 --> 00:44:02,231\r\nMerry Christmas. I'm ringing.\r\n\r\n498\r\n00:44:02,360 --> 00:44:04,316\r\nYeah? Yeah?!\r\n\r\n499\r\n00:44:04,440 --> 00:44:05,509\r\nWhere?\r\n\r\n500\r\n00:44:05,640 --> 00:44:06,834\r\nYou bet!\r\n\r\n501\r\n00:44:06,960 --> 00:44:11,112\r\nSomebody watch my line. There's\r\na swingin' party on the 19th floor!\r\n\r\n502\r\n00:44:13,360 --> 00:44:16,238\r\n<i>~ Oh, what fun it is to ride</i>\r\n<i>in a one-horse open sleigh ~</i>\r\n\r\n503\r\n00:44:16,360 --> 00:44:19,955\r\n<i>~ Hey! Jingle bells,</i>\r\n<i>jingle bells, jingle all the way ~</i>\r\n\r\n504\r\n00:44:20,080 --> 00:44:23,231\r\n<i>~ Oh, what fun it is to ride</i>\r\n<i>in a one-horse open sleigh ~</i>\r\n\r\n505\r\n00:44:38,720 --> 00:44:43,919\r\nSo I said to him \"Never again. Either you\r\nget yourself a bigger car or a smaller girl.\"\r\n\r\n506\r\n00:44:44,760 --> 00:44:46,716\r\nMiss Kubelik? Miss...\r\n\r\n507\r\n00:44:46,960 --> 00:44:49,076\r\n- Merry Christmas.\r\n- Thank you.\r\n\r\n508\r\n00:44:49,200 --> 00:44:52,158\r\n- I thought you were avoiding me.\r\n- What gave you that idea?\r\n\r\n509\r\n00:44:52,280 --> 00:44:55,909\r\nIn six weeks you've only been in my\r\nelevator once, and you kept on your hat.\r\n\r\n510\r\n00:44:56,040 --> 00:44:59,350\r\nAs a matter of fact, I was rather hurt\r\nthat night you stood me up.\r\n\r\n511\r\n00:44:59,480 --> 00:45:01,436\r\nI don't blame you. It was unforgivable.\r\n\r\n512\r\n00:45:01,560 --> 00:45:03,118\r\n- I forgive you.\r\n- You shouldn't.\r\n\r\n513\r\n00:45:03,240 --> 00:45:06,596\r\nYou couldn't help it. You can't\r\nsuddenly walk out on one man...\r\n\r\n514\r\n00:45:06,720 --> 00:45:08,870\r\n...because you have a date\r\nwith another man.\r\n\r\n515\r\n00:45:09,000 --> 00:45:11,275\r\n- You did the decent thing.\r\n- Don't be too sure.\r\n\r\n516\r\n00:45:11,400 --> 00:45:14,756\r\nJust because I wear a uniform,\r\nthat doesn't make me a Girl Scout.\r\n\r\n517\r\n00:45:14,880 --> 00:45:19,431\r\nA second administrative assistant has\r\nto be a pretty good judge of character.\r\n\r\n518\r\n00:45:19,560 --> 00:45:21,949\r\nAnd as far as I'm concerned, you're tops.\r\n\r\n519\r\n00:45:22,080 --> 00:45:26,596\r\nI mean decencywise and... otherwisewise.\r\n\r\n520\r\n00:45:26,720 --> 00:45:28,120\r\nCheers.\r\n\r\n521\r\n00:45:30,360 --> 00:45:32,590\r\n- One more.\r\n- I shouldn't drink while driving.\r\n\r\n522\r\n00:45:32,720 --> 00:45:37,635\r\nYou're so right. By the power vested\r\nin me, I declare this elevator out of order.\r\n\r\n523\r\n00:45:37,760 --> 00:45:40,035\r\nShall we join the natives?\r\n\r\n524\r\n00:45:40,160 --> 00:45:43,550\r\n- Why not? They seem friendly enough.\r\n- Don't you believe it.\r\n\r\n525\r\n00:45:43,680 --> 00:45:47,639\r\nThere'll be human sacrifices. White-collar\r\nworkers tossed into computers...\r\n\r\n526\r\n00:45:47,760 --> 00:45:49,910\r\n...and punched full of little square holes.\r\n\r\n527\r\n00:45:50,040 --> 00:45:52,156\r\n- How many drinks did you have?\r\n- Three!\r\n\r\n528\r\n00:45:52,280 --> 00:45:55,352\r\n- I thought so.\r\n- Wait. I hear the sound of running water.\r\n\r\n529\r\n00:45:55,480 --> 00:45:57,948\r\n- I'll be right back!\r\n- I'll be right here.\r\n\r\n530\r\n00:45:59,360 --> 00:46:00,360\r\nHi!\r\n\r\n531\r\n00:46:01,080 --> 00:46:03,594\r\nHow's the branch manager\r\nfrom Kansas City?\r\n\r\n532\r\n00:46:03,720 --> 00:46:05,358\r\n- I beg your pardon?\r\n- I'm Miss Olsen.\r\n\r\n533\r\n00:46:05,480 --> 00:46:07,357\r\nMr Sheldrake's secretary.\r\n\r\n534\r\n00:46:07,480 --> 00:46:09,755\r\nSo you don't have to\r\nplay innocent with me.\r\n\r\n535\r\n00:46:09,880 --> 00:46:13,759\r\nHe used to tell his wife\r\nI was the branch manager from Seattle...\r\n\r\n536\r\n00:46:13,880 --> 00:46:17,953\r\n...four years ago when we were having\r\na little ring-a-ding-ding.\r\n\r\n537\r\n00:46:18,880 --> 00:46:22,839\r\n- I don't know what you're talking about.\r\n- Before me it was Miss Rossi in Auditing.\r\n\r\n538\r\n00:46:22,960 --> 00:46:25,520\r\nAnd after me it was\r\nMiss Koch in Disability.\r\n\r\n539\r\n00:46:25,640 --> 00:46:27,915\r\nAnd right before you was a Miss, um...\r\n\r\n540\r\n00:46:28,040 --> 00:46:30,315\r\nOh, what's her name? On the 25th floor.\r\n\r\n541\r\n00:46:30,440 --> 00:46:33,876\r\n- Would you excuse me?\r\n- What for? You haven't done anything.\r\n\r\n542\r\n00:46:34,080 --> 00:46:37,072\r\nIt's him. Oh, what a salesman!\r\n\r\n543\r\n00:46:37,560 --> 00:46:39,915\r\nAlways the last booth\r\nin the Chinese restaurant...\r\n\r\n544\r\n00:46:40,040 --> 00:46:42,998\r\n...and the same pitch\r\nabout divorcing his wife.\r\n\r\n545\r\n00:46:45,040 --> 00:46:49,318\r\nThen, in the end, you wind up\r\nwith egg foo yung on your face.\r\n\r\n546\r\n00:46:49,440 --> 00:46:51,396\r\nMiss Kubelik!\r\n\r\n547\r\n00:46:53,400 --> 00:46:55,118\r\nWell, thank you, Miss Olsen.\r\n\r\n548\r\n00:46:55,240 --> 00:46:59,199\r\nAlways happy to do a little something\r\nfor our girls in uniform.\r\n\r\n549\r\n00:47:00,360 --> 00:47:02,430\r\nAre you all right? What's the matter?\r\n\r\n550\r\n00:47:02,560 --> 00:47:05,028\r\nNothing. There are just\r\ntoo many people here.\r\n\r\n551\r\n00:47:05,160 --> 00:47:08,948\r\nWhy don't we step into my office? There's\r\nsomething I want your opinion about.\r\n\r\n552\r\n00:47:09,080 --> 00:47:13,676\r\nI have my own office now. I'm the second\r\nyoungest executive in this company.\r\n\r\n553\r\n00:47:13,800 --> 00:47:17,349\r\nThe only one younger is a grandson\r\nof the chairman of the board.\r\n\r\n554\r\n00:47:18,560 --> 00:47:20,516\r\nDo you mind?\r\n\r\n555\r\n00:47:24,560 --> 00:47:27,916\r\nMiss Kubelik, I would like\r\nyour honest opinion.\r\n\r\n556\r\n00:47:28,040 --> 00:47:31,191\r\nI've had this under my desk\r\nfor a week. It cost me $15.\r\n\r\n557\r\n00:47:31,320 --> 00:47:34,471\r\nI haven't been able\r\nto get up enough nerve to wear it.\r\n\r\n558\r\n00:47:39,920 --> 00:47:44,675\r\nIt's what they call the Junior Executive\r\nmodel. What do you think?\r\n\r\n559\r\n00:47:47,960 --> 00:47:50,793\r\nI guess I made a boo-boo, huh?\r\n\r\n560\r\n00:47:50,920 --> 00:47:53,070\r\n- I like it.\r\n- Really?\r\n\r\n561\r\n00:47:53,200 --> 00:47:55,998\r\nYou wouldn't be ashamed to be seen\r\nwith somebody in this hat?\r\n\r\n562\r\n00:47:56,120 --> 00:47:59,954\r\n- Of course not.\r\n- Maybe if I wore it a little to one side.\r\n\r\n563\r\n00:48:00,080 --> 00:48:02,719\r\n- Is that better?\r\n- Much better.\r\n\r\n564\r\n00:48:02,840 --> 00:48:05,434\r\nSince you wouldn't be\r\nashamed to be seen with me...\r\n\r\n565\r\n00:48:05,560 --> 00:48:08,552\r\n...how about goin' out tonight -\r\nyou, me and the bowler?\r\n\r\n566\r\n00:48:08,680 --> 00:48:11,399\r\nWe'll stroll down 5th Avenue,\r\nsort of break it in.\r\n\r\n567\r\n00:48:11,520 --> 00:48:15,195\r\n- This is a bad day for me.\r\n- I understand. Christmas and family.\r\n\r\n568\r\n00:48:15,320 --> 00:48:17,629\r\nI'd better get back to my elevator\r\nor I'll be fired.\r\n\r\n569\r\n00:48:17,760 --> 00:48:21,435\r\nDon't worry about that. I've got\r\nquite a bit of influence with Personnel.\r\n\r\n570\r\n00:48:21,560 --> 00:48:23,516\r\nYou know Mr Sheldrake?\r\n\r\n571\r\n00:48:24,960 --> 00:48:27,235\r\n- Why?\r\n- He and I are like that.\r\n\r\n572\r\n00:48:27,360 --> 00:48:29,920\r\nSent me a Christmas card. See?\r\n\r\n573\r\n00:48:35,400 --> 00:48:38,039\r\nMakes a cute picture.\r\n\r\n574\r\n00:48:38,960 --> 00:48:41,554\r\nI could talk to Mr Sheldrake.\r\nGet you a promotion.\r\n\r\n575\r\n00:48:41,680 --> 00:48:47,152\r\n- Would you like to be an elevator starter?\r\n- Too many girls have seniority over me.\r\n\r\n576\r\n00:48:47,560 --> 00:48:50,518\r\nNo problem. Why don't we\r\ndiscuss it over the holidays?\r\n\r\n577\r\n00:48:50,640 --> 00:48:54,872\r\nI could call you, pick you up, have\r\na big unveiling. Am I wearing this right?\r\n\r\n578\r\n00:48:55,000 --> 00:48:57,070\r\nI think so. Here.\r\n\r\n579\r\n00:48:57,200 --> 00:49:00,112\r\nIt's not tilted too much?\r\nThis is a conservative firm.\r\n\r\n580\r\n00:49:00,240 --> 00:49:03,198\r\nI don't want people\r\nto think I'm an entertainer.\r\n\r\n581\r\n00:49:07,480 --> 00:49:09,436\r\nWhat's the matter?\r\n\r\n582\r\n00:49:12,080 --> 00:49:14,469\r\n- The mirror. It's broken.\r\n- Yes, I know.\r\n\r\n583\r\n00:49:15,520 --> 00:49:18,432\r\nI like it that way.\r\nMakes me look the way I feel.\r\n\r\n584\r\n00:49:22,560 --> 00:49:24,516\r\nYour phone.\r\n\r\n585\r\n00:49:29,960 --> 00:49:30,960\r\nYes?\r\n\r\n586\r\n00:49:32,480 --> 00:49:34,232\r\nUh, just a minute.\r\n\r\n587\r\n00:49:34,360 --> 00:49:38,717\r\n- If you don't mind, this is sort of personal.\r\n- Have a nice Christmas.\r\n\r\n588\r\n00:49:45,200 --> 00:49:47,156\r\nYes, Mr Sheldrake.\r\n\r\n589\r\n00:49:48,200 --> 00:49:53,320\r\nNo, I didn't forget. The tree is up and the\r\nTom and Jerry mix is in the refrigerator.\r\n\r\n590\r\n00:49:53,440 --> 00:49:55,396\r\nYes, sir. Same to you.\r\n\r\n591\r\n00:50:21,560 --> 00:50:23,949\r\nHey! Where are you goin', Buddy-boy?\r\n\r\n592\r\n00:50:24,080 --> 00:50:26,230\r\nThe party's just starting.\r\n\r\n593\r\n00:50:26,360 --> 00:50:29,636\r\nListen, kid. Gimme a break.\r\nHow about tomorrow afternoon?\r\n\r\n594\r\n00:50:29,760 --> 00:50:35,039\r\nI can't take her to that drive-in again.\r\nThe car has no heater. Four o'clock. OK?\r\n\r\n595\r\n00:51:09,800 --> 00:51:15,158\r\nHey, Charlie! Gimme a shot of bourbon,\r\nand step on it! My sleigh is double-parked!\r\n\r\n596\r\n00:52:19,720 --> 00:52:22,792\r\nYou buy me a drink,\r\nI'll buy you some music.\r\n\r\n597\r\n00:52:22,920 --> 00:52:24,876\r\nRum Collins.\r\n\r\n598\r\n00:52:34,600 --> 00:52:35,600\r\nUh...\r\n\r\n599\r\n00:52:36,000 --> 00:52:39,470\r\nRum Collins and...\r\nanother one of these little mothers.\r\n\r\n600\r\n00:52:51,120 --> 00:52:52,997\r\nYou like Castro?\r\n\r\n601\r\n00:52:53,120 --> 00:52:55,839\r\nI mean, how do you feel about Castro?\r\n\r\n602\r\n00:52:55,960 --> 00:52:59,635\r\n- What is Castro?\r\n- You know. That big shot down in Cuba.\r\n\r\n603\r\n00:52:59,760 --> 00:53:01,830\r\n- With the crazy beard.\r\n- What about him?\r\n\r\n604\r\n00:53:01,960 --> 00:53:05,111\r\nCos as far as I'm concerned,\r\nhe's a no-good fink.\r\n\r\n605\r\n00:53:05,240 --> 00:53:08,471\r\nTwo weeks ago I wrote him a letter.\r\nNever even answered me.\r\n\r\n606\r\n00:53:08,600 --> 00:53:09,590\r\nThat so?\r\n\r\n607\r\n00:53:09,690 --> 00:53:13,355\r\nAll I wanted him to do was\r\nlet Mickey out for Christmas.\r\n\r\n608\r\n00:53:13,480 --> 00:53:15,436\r\n- Who's Mickey?\r\n- My husband.\r\n\r\n609\r\n00:53:15,560 --> 00:53:18,028\r\nHe's in Havana, in jail.\r\n\r\n610\r\n00:53:18,160 --> 00:53:21,550\r\n- Mixed up in that revolution?\r\n- Mickey would do nothin' like that.\r\n\r\n611\r\n00:53:21,680 --> 00:53:25,309\r\nHe's a jockey.\r\nThey caught him dopin' a horse.\r\n\r\n612\r\n00:53:25,440 --> 00:53:27,590\r\nWell, you can't win 'em all.\r\n\r\n613\r\n00:53:32,560 --> 00:53:36,075\r\n'Twas the night before Christmas,\r\nand all through the house\r\n\r\n614\r\n00:53:36,200 --> 00:53:38,156\r\nNot a creature was stirrin'...\r\n\r\n615\r\n00:53:38,920 --> 00:53:41,878\r\nNothin'. No action.\r\n\r\n616\r\n00:53:42,400 --> 00:53:44,231\r\nDullsville.\r\n\r\n617\r\n00:53:44,360 --> 00:53:46,396\r\n- You married?\r\n- No.\r\n\r\n618\r\n00:53:46,520 --> 00:53:48,476\r\n- Family?\r\n- No.\r\n\r\n619\r\n00:53:49,280 --> 00:53:53,637\r\nA night like this, it sort of spooks you\r\nto walk into an empty apartment.\r\n\r\n620\r\n00:53:55,160 --> 00:53:59,119\r\nI said I had no family. I didn't say\r\nI had an empty apartment.\r\n\r\n621\r\n00:54:03,800 --> 00:54:06,155\r\nCome on, Fran. Don't be that way.\r\n\r\n622\r\n00:54:06,840 --> 00:54:09,718\r\nAre you just gonna\r\nsit there and keep bawling?\r\n\r\n623\r\n00:54:09,840 --> 00:54:12,991\r\nYou won't talk to me?\r\nYou won't tell me what's wrong?\r\n\r\n624\r\n00:54:14,680 --> 00:54:19,549\r\nI know you think I'm stalling you but...\r\nwhen you've been married for 12 years...\r\n\r\n625\r\n00:54:19,680 --> 00:54:24,071\r\n...you just don't sit down to breakfast and\r\nsay \"Pass the sugar. I want a divorce.\"\r\n\r\n626\r\n00:54:24,200 --> 00:54:26,668\r\nIt's not that easy.\r\n\r\n627\r\n00:54:27,880 --> 00:54:32,510\r\nAnyway, this is the wrong time. The kids\r\nare off school, my in-laws are visiting.\r\n\r\n628\r\n00:54:32,640 --> 00:54:34,596\r\nI can't bring it up now.\r\n\r\n629\r\n00:54:36,320 --> 00:54:41,189\r\nThis isn't like you, Fran. You were always\r\nsuch a good sport. Such fun to be with.\r\n\r\n630\r\n00:54:43,440 --> 00:54:47,638\r\nThat's me. The happy idiot.\r\nA million laughs.\r\n\r\n631\r\n00:54:48,560 --> 00:54:52,633\r\nWell, that's a little more like it.\r\nAt least you're speaking to me.\r\n\r\n632\r\n00:54:53,560 --> 00:54:56,870\r\nA funny thing happened to me\r\nat the office party today.\r\n\r\n633\r\n00:54:57,000 --> 00:54:59,355\r\nI ran into your secretary, Miss Olsen.\r\n\r\n634\r\n00:55:00,320 --> 00:55:02,276\r\nYou know. Ring-a-ding-ding?\r\n\r\n635\r\n00:55:03,320 --> 00:55:06,073\r\nAnd I laughed so much, I like to died.\r\n\r\n636\r\n00:55:06,200 --> 00:55:10,637\r\nIs that what's been bothering you, Fran?\r\nMiss Olsen? That's ancient history.\r\n\r\n637\r\n00:55:10,760 --> 00:55:13,718\r\nWell, I never was very good at history.\r\n\r\n638\r\n00:55:14,400 --> 00:55:18,473\r\nLet me see. There was Miss Olsen,\r\nand then there was Miss Rossi.\r\n\r\n639\r\n00:55:18,600 --> 00:55:21,592\r\nNo, she came before.\r\nMiss Koch came after Miss Olsen.\r\n\r\n640\r\n00:55:21,720 --> 00:55:24,029\r\n- Now, Fran...\r\n- And just think.\r\n\r\n641\r\n00:55:24,160 --> 00:55:27,869\r\nRight now some lucky girl in the building\r\nis gonna come after me.\r\n\r\n642\r\n00:55:28,000 --> 00:55:30,639\r\nOK. OK, Fran. I guess I deserved that.\r\n\r\n643\r\n00:55:30,760 --> 00:55:34,719\r\nBut ask yourself: Why does a man\r\nrun around with a lot of girls?\r\n\r\n644\r\n00:55:34,840 --> 00:55:38,469\r\nBecause he's unhappy at home.\r\nBecause he's lonely. That's why.\r\n\r\n645\r\n00:55:38,600 --> 00:55:41,717\r\nBut that was before you, Fran.\r\nI've stopped running.\r\n\r\n646\r\n00:55:43,200 --> 00:55:47,159\r\nHow could I be so stupid?\r\nYou'd think I would've learned by now.\r\n\r\n647\r\n00:55:47,280 --> 00:55:51,637\r\nWhen you're in love with a married man,\r\nyou shouldn't wear mascara.\r\n\r\n648\r\n00:55:52,360 --> 00:55:55,352\r\nIt's Christmas Eve, Fran.\r\nLet's not fight, huh?\r\n\r\n649\r\n00:55:57,560 --> 00:55:59,915\r\n- Merry Christmas.\r\n- What is it?\r\n\r\n650\r\n00:56:05,200 --> 00:56:07,760\r\nOh. Our friend at the Chinese restaurant.\r\n\r\n651\r\n00:56:08,960 --> 00:56:14,034\r\n- Thanks, Fran. We'd better keep it here.\r\n- Yeah, we'd better.\r\n\r\n652\r\n00:56:14,760 --> 00:56:16,796\r\nOh, I have a present for you.\r\n\r\n653\r\n00:56:16,920 --> 00:56:21,118\r\nI didn't know what to get you. Besides,\r\nit's kind of awkward for me shopping, so...\r\n\r\n654\r\n00:56:21,240 -->